par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 101.4}{\f0\insrsid3761202 b}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  The Two-Headed Giant variant uses the }{\f0\insrsid3761202 multiplayer}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  mulligan rule, with some modifications. First, the starting team takes any mulligans. For a team to take a mulligan, each player on that team decides whether or not to take a mulligan, then all players who chose to do so take their mulligans at the same time. The first time a player takes a mulligan, he or she draws a new hand of seven cards. After each player on that team who took a mulligan looks at his or her new hand, the team repeats the process. (Subsequent hands decrease by one card as normal.) Once a player has decided to keep a hand, those cards become his or her opening hand}{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 .}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  That player can\rquote t take any more mulligans, but his or her teammate may. Once each player on the starting team decides to keep an opening hand, the other team may take mulligans.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example: }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Bob and Clare are the starting team in a Two-Headed Giant game. They each draw seven cards. After reviewing each other\rquote s hands, both Bob and Clare decide to mulligan. Each shuffles his or her hand into his or her deck and draws seven cards. Clare isn\rquote t sure about Bob\rquote s new hand, but he decides to keep it. Clare decides to take another mulligan. Bob\rquote s hand becomes his opening hand, and Clare shuffles her hand into her deck and draws six cards. Then only Clare has the option to mulligan. She decides to keep her hand of six cards and that becomes her opening hand. After that, the other team decides whether to take mulligans.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 101.5. Once all players have kept their opening hands, }{\f0\insrsid3761202 if any cards in the starting player\rquote s hand allow that player to begin the game with those cards in play, he or she may put any or all of them into play. Then each other player, in turn order, may do the same.\par \par 101.6. T}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 he starting player takes his or her first turn.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK7}\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 101.}{\f0\insrsid3761202 6}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 a In a two-player game, the player who plays first skips the draw step (see rule 304, \ldblquote Draw Step\rdblquote ) of his or her first turn. \par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK30}101.}{\f0\insrsid3761202 6}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 b In a Two-Headed Giant game, the team who plays first skips the draw step of their first turn. In all other multiplayer games, no player skips the draw step of his or her first turn. \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK30}\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 102. Winning and Losing\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 102.1. A game ends immediately when either a player wins or the game is a draw. \par \par 102.2. There are several ways to win the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 102.2a A player still in the game wins the game if all of that player\rquote s opponents have lost the game.\par \par 102.2b An effect may state that a player wins the game. (In certain multiplayer games, this may not cause the game to end; see rule 102.3g.)\par \par 102.2c In a multiplayer game between teams, a team with at least one player still in the game wins the game if all other teams have lost the game. Each player on the winning team wins the game, even if one or more of those players had previously lost that game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 102.3. There are several ways to lose the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 102.3a A player can concede the game at any time. A player who concedes loses the game immediately.\par \par 102.3b If a player\rquote s life total is 0 or less, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par 102.3c When a player is required to draw more cards than are left in his or her library, he or she draws the remaining cards, and then loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par 102.3d If a player has ten or more poison counters, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par 102.3e If a player would both win and lose simultaneously, he or she loses.\par \par 102.3f In a multiplayer game between teams, a team loses the game if all players on that team have lost.\par \par 102.3g In a multiplayer game using the limited range of influence option, an effect that states that a player wins the game instead causes all of that player\rquote s opponents within his or her range of influence to lose the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 102.4. There are several ways to draw the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 102.4a If all the players remaining in a game lose simultaneously, the game is a draw.\par \par 102.4b If the game somehow enters a \ldblquote loop,\rdblquote  repeating a sequence of events with no way to stop, the game is a draw. Loops that contain an optional action don\rquote t result in a draw.\par \par 102.4c In a multiplayer game between teams, the game is a draw if all remaining teams lose at once.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 102.5. If a player loses the game, he or she leaves the game. Likewise, if a player leaves the game, he or she loses the game. The multiplayer rules handle what happens when a player leaves the game; see rule 600.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 103. The }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Golden Rules\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 103.1. Whenever a card\rquote s text directly contradicts these rules, the card takes precedence. The card overrides only the rule that applies to that specific situation. The only exception is that a player can concede the game at any time (see rule 102.3a).\par \par 103.2. When a rule or effect says something can happen and another effect says it can\rquote t, the \ldblquote can\rquote t\rdblquote  effect wins. For example, if one effect reads \ldblquote You may play an additional land this turn\rdblquote  and another reads \ldblquote You can\rquote t play land cards this turn,\rdblquote  the effect that keeps you from playing lands wins out. Note that adding abilities to objects and removing abilities from objects don\rquote t fall under this rule. See rule 407, \ldblquote Adding and Removing Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par 103.3. If an instruction requires taking an impossible action, it\rquote s ignored. (In many cases the card will specify consequences for this; if it doesn\rquote t, there\rquote s no effect.)\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK6}103.4. If multiple players would make choices and/or take actions at the same time, the active player (the player whose turn it is) makes any choices required, then the next player in turn order (usually the player seated to the active player\rquote s left) makes any choices required, followed by the remaining nonactive players in turn order. Then the actions happen simultaneously. This rule is often referred to as the \ldblquote Active Player, Nonactive Player (APNAP) order\rdblquote  rule.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A card reads \ldblquote Each player sacrifices a creature.\rdblquote  First, the active player chooses a creature he or she controls. Then each of the nonactive players chooses a creature he or she controls. Then all creatures are sacrificed simultaneously.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 103.4a A player knows the choices made by the previous players when he or she makes his or her choice.\par \par 103.4b If a player would make more than one choice at the same time, the player makes the choices in the order written, or in the order he or she chooses if the choices aren\rquote t ordered.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK6}\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 104. Numbers and Symbols\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 104.1. The }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  game uses only integers.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 104.1a You can\rquote t choose a fractional number, deal fractional damage, gain fractional life, and so on. If a spell or ability could generate a fractional number, the spell or ability will tell you whether to round up or down.\par \par 104.1b Most of the time, the }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  game uses only positive numbers. You can\rquote t choose a negative number, deal negative damage, gain negative life, and so on. However, it\rquote s possible for a game value, such as a creature\rquote s power, to be less than zero. If a calculation or comparison that would determine the result of an effect needs to use a negative value, it does so. If such a calculation yields a negative number, zero is used instead, unless that effect sets a creature\rquote s power or toughness, changes a creature\rquote s power or toughness, or sets a player\rquote s life total.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If a 3/4 creature gets -5/-0, it\rquote s a -2/4 creature. It deals no damage in combat. Its total power and toughness is 2. You\rquote d have to give it +3/+0 to raise its power to 1.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Viridian Joiner is a 1/2 creature that says \ldblquote \{T\}: Add an amount of \{G\} to your mana pool equal to Viridian Joiner\rquote s power.\rdblquote  An effect gives it -2/-0, then its ability is activated. The ability adds no mana to your mana pool.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 104.2. If anything needs to use a number that can\rquote t be determined, either as a result or in a calculation, it uses 0 instea