pha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 203. Mana Cost and Color\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 203.1. The mana cost of a card is indicated by mana symbols near the top of the card. On most cards, these symbols are printed in the upper right corner. Some cards from the }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Future Sight}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  set have alternate frames in which the mana symbols appear to the left of the art. Paying an object\rquote s mana cost requires matching the color of any colored mana symbols as well as paying the generic mana indicated in the cost.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 203.1a A copy of an object copies that object\rquote s mana cost. See rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects.\rdblquote \par \par 203.1b }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Some cards have no mana symbols where their mana cost would appear. This represents an }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 unpayable cost.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 An ability can also have an unpayable cost if its cost is based on the mana cost of a spell with no mana cost. Attempting to play a spell or ability that has an unpayable cost is a legal action. However, attempting to pay an unpayable cost is an illegal action.\par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525           }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 If an unpayable cost is increased by an effect or an additional cost is imposed, the cost is still unpayable. If an alternative cost is applied to an unpayable cost, including an effect that allows you to play a spell without paying its mana cost, the alternative cost may be paid.\par \par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 203.1c }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Lands normally have no mana cost. Lands are played without paying any costs.\par \par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 203.1d Tokens have no mana cost unless the effect that creates them specifies otherwise.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 203.2. An object is the color or colors of the mana symbols in its mana cost, regardless of the color of its frame.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 203.2a Objects with no colored mana symbols in their mana costs are colorless.\par \par 203.2b An object with two or more different colored mana symbols in its mana cost is each of the colors of those mana symbols. Most multicolored cards are printed with a gold frame, but this is not a requirement for a card to be multicolored.\par \par 203.2c The five colors are white, blue, black, red, and green. The white mana symbol is represented by \{W\}, blue by \{U\}, black by \{B\}, red by \{R\}, and green by \{G\}.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An object with a mana cost of \{2\}\{W\} is white, an object with a mana cost of \{2\} is colorless, and one with a mana cost of \{2\}\{W\}\{B\} is both white and black.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 203.2d If a player is asked to choose a color, he or she must choose one of the five colors. \ldblquote Multicolored\rdblquote  is not a color.\par \par 203.2e An object with one or more hybrid mana symbols in its mana cost is each of the colors of that mana symbol, in addition to any other colors the object might be. Most cards with hybrid mana symbols in their mana costs are printed in a two-tone frame. See rule 104.3f.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 203.3. The converted mana cost of an object is a number equal to the total amount of mana in its mana cost, regardless of color. Some effects ask a player to pay mana equal to an object\rquote s converted mana cost; this cost may be paid with any combination of colored and/or colorless mana, regardless of the colors in the object\rquote s mana cost.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A mana cost of \{3\}\{U\}\{U\} translates to a converted mana cost of 5.}{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 203.3a The converted mana cost of an object with no mana cost is 0.\par \par 203.3b When calculating the converted mana cost of an object with an \{X\} in its mana cost, X is treated as 0 while the object is not on the stack, and X is treated as the number chosen for it while the object is on the stack.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 203.4. Any additional cost listed in an object\rquote s rules text or imposed by an effect isn\rquote t part of the mana cost. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote ) Such costs are paid at the same time as the spell\rquote s other costs.\par  \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 204. Illustration\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 204.1. The illustration is printed on the upper half of a card and has no game significance. For example, a creature doesn\rquote t have the flying ability unless stated in its rules text, even if it\rquote s depicted as flying.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 205. Type Line\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 205.1. The }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type (and subtype and supertype, if applicable) of a card is printed directly below the illustration. (See rule 212, \ldblquote }{\f0\insrsid3761202 Card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Type, Supertype, and Subtype.\rdblquote )\par \par 205.2. }{\f0\insrsid3761202 Card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Types\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 205.2a The }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 types are artifact, creature, enchantment, instant, land, }{\f0\insrsid3761202 planeswalker, }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 sorcery, and tribal.\par \par 205.2b Some objects have more than one }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type (for example, an artifact creature). Such objects satisfy the criteria for any effect that applies to any of their}{\f0\insrsid3761202  card}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  types.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 205.3. Subtypes\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 205.3a A card can have one or more subtypes printed on its type line.\par \par 205.3b Subtypes are always single words and are listed after a long dash. Each word after the dash is a separate subtype.\par \par 205.3c Subtypes of a [}{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type] object are also called }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 [}{\i\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type] types. }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 For example, creature subtypes are also called creature types. Objects may have multiple subtypes.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  \ldblquote Basic Land \emdash  Mountain\rdblquote  means the card is a land with the Mountain subtype. \ldblquote Creature \emdash  Goblin Wizard\rdblquote  means the card is a creature with the subtypes Goblin and Wizard. \ldblquote Artifact \emdash  Equipment\rdblquote  means the card is an artifact with the subtype Equipment.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 205.3d Artifact, enchantment, land}{\f0\insrsid3761202 , and planeswalker}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  each have their own unique set of possible subtypes. Instant and sorcery share their lists of subtypes; these subtypes are called }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 spell types.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Creature and tribal also share their lists of subtypes; these subtypes are called }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 creature types.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  (You can find complete lists of subtypes in the glossary at the end of this document under \ldblquote Creature Types,\rdblquote  \ldblquote Land Types,\rdblquote  and so on.)\par \par 205.3e If a card with multiple}{\f0\insrsid3761202  card}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  types has one or more subtypes, each subtype is correlated to its appropriate }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Dryad Arbor\rquote s type line says \ldblquote Land Creature \emdash  Forest Dryad.\rdblquote  Forest is a land type, and Dryad is a creature type.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 205.4. Supertypes\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 205.4a A card can also have one or more }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 supertypes.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  These are printed directly before its card types. If an object\rquote s }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 types or subtypes change, any supertypes it has are kept, although they may not be relevant to the new}{\f0\insrsid3761202  card}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  type.\par \par 205.4b Any land with the supertype \ldblquote basic\rdblquote  is a basic land. Any land that doesn\rquote t have this supertype is a nonbasic land.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Note that cards printed in sets prior to the }{\i0\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Eighth Edition}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  core set didn\rquote t use the word \ldblquote basic\rdblquote  to indicate a basic land. Cards from those sets with the following names are basic lands: Forest, Island, Mountain, Plains, Swamp, Snow-Covered Forest, Snow-Covered Island, Snow-Covered Mountain, Snow-Covered Plains, and Snow-Covered Swamp.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 205.4c Any permanent with the supertype \ldblquote legendary\rdblquote  is subject to the state-based effect for legendary permanents, also called the \ldblquote legend rule\rdblquote  (see rule 420.5e).\par \par 205.4d Any permanent with the supertype \ldblquote world\rdblquote  is subject to the state-based effect for world permanents, also called the \ldblquote world rule\rdblquote  (see rule 420.5i).\par \par 205.4e Any permanent with the supertype \ldblquote snow\rdblquote  is a snow permanent. Any permanent that doesn\rquote t have this supertype is a nonsnow permanent, regardless of its name.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 206. Expansion Symbol\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 206.1. The expansion symbol indicates which }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  set a card is from. It\rquote s normally printed below the right edge of the illustration.\par \par 206.2. The color of the expansion symbol indicates the rarity of the card within its set. A gold symbol indicates the card is rare. A silver expansion symbol indicates the card is uncommon. A black or white expansion symbol indicates the card is common or is a basic land. A purple expansion symbol signifies a special rarity; to date, only the }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Time Spiral\u8482\'aa}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  \ldblquote timeshifted\rdblquote  cards, which were rarer than that set\rquote s rare cards, have had purple expansion symbols. (Prior to the }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Exodus\u8482\'aa}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  set, all expansion symbols were black, regardless of rarity. Also, prior to the }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Sixth Edition}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  core set, }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  core sets didn\rquote t have expansion symbols at all.)\par \par 206.3. A spell or ability that affects cards from a particular set \ldblquote looks\rdblquote  only for that set\rquote s expansion symbol. A card reprinted in the core set receives the core set\rquote s expansion symbol. Any reprinted version of the card no longer counts as part of its original set unless it was reprinted with that set\rquote s expansion symbol. The first five editions of the core set had no expansion symbol.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 207. Text Box\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 207.1. The text box is printed on the lower half of the card. It usually contains rules text defining the card\rquote s abilities.\par \par 207.2. The text box may also contain italicized reminder text (in parentheses), which summarizes a rule that applies to that card, and italicized flavor text, which has no game function, but like the illustration, adds artistic appeal to the game.\par \par 207.3. A guild icon appears in the text box of many }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Ravnica\u174\'a8}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  block cards. These cards either have the specified guild\rqu