quote t legally be attached to an object that isn\rquote t a land. Rules 212.2h\endash k apply to Fortifications in relation to lands just as they apply to Equipment in relation to creatures. Fortification\rquote s analog to the equip keyword ability is the fortify keyword ability. (See rule 502.65, \ldblquote Fortify.\rdblquote )\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 212.3. Creatures\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 212.3a A player }{\f0\insrsid3761202 who has priority }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 may play a creature card from his or her hand during a main phase of his or her turn when the stack is empty. Playing a creature as a spell uses the stack. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 212.3b When a creature spell resolves, its controller puts it into play under his or her control.\par \par 212.3c Creature subtypes are always a single word and are listed after a long dash: \ldblquote Creature \emdash  Human Soldier,\rdblquote  \ldblquote Artifact Creature \emdash  Golem,\rdblquote  and so on. Creature subtypes are also called creature types. Creatures may have multiple subtypes. (You can find the complete list of creature subtypes under \ldblquote Creature Types\rdblquote  in the glossary at the end of this document.)\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  \ldblquote Creature \emdash  Goblin Wizard\rdblquote  means the card is a creature with the subt