Some abilities that are not followed when the spell resolves are activated abilities or triggered abilities, any abilities that define the zone from which it can be played (see rule 401.4), any abilities that apply while the spell is in a zone from which it can be played (see rule 401.5), or any abilities that apply while the spell is on the stack (see rule 401.6).\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 401.4. Any object can have static abilities that allow it to be played from a zone other than a player\rquote s hand. These abilities are active while the object is in that zone.\par \par 401.5. Any object can have static abilities that apply while the object is in a zone from which it can be played. These include restrictions on playing the object and abilities that allow the object to be played at a time that it otherwise could not or in a manner that it otherwise could not.\par \par 401.6. Any spell can have static abilities that apply while the spell is on the stack. These include, but are not limited to, additional costs, alternative costs, and cost reductions. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par 401.7. As the final part of an instant or sorcery spell\rquote s resolution, the card is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. As the final part of an artifact, creature, enchantment}{\f0\insrsid3761202 , or planeswalker}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  spell\rquote s resolution, the card becomes a permanent and is put into the in-play zone under the control of the spell\rquote s controller. (See rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote ) If any spell is countered, the card is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard as part of the resolution of the countering spell or ability.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 402. Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 402.1. An ability is text on an object that\rquote s not reminder text or flavor text (see rule 400.1). The result of following such an instruction is an effect. (See rule 416, \ldblquote Effects.\rdblquote ) Abilities can affect the objects they\rquote re on; they can also affect other objects and/or players. Abilities can grant abilities to other objects or to the objects they\rquote re on; they do so when the words \ldblquote has,\rdblquote  \ldblquote have,\rdblquote  \ldblquote gains,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote gain\rdblquote  are used.\par \par 402.2. There are three general categories of abilities: activated, triggered, and static. Activated and triggered abilities can also be mana abilities. Abilities can generate one-shot effects or continuous effects. Some effects are replacement effects or prevention effects.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK26}402.3. Abilities can be beneficial or detrimental.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  \ldblquote [This creature] can\rquote t block\rdblquote  is an ability.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK26}\par 402.4. An additional cost or alternative cost to play a card is an ability of the card.\par \par 402.5. An ability isn\rquote t a spell and therefore can\rquote t be countered by anything that counters only spells. Abilities can be countered by effects that specifically counter abilities, as well as by the rules (for example, an ability with one or more targets is countered if all its targets become illegal).\par \par 402.6. Once activated or triggered, an ability exists independently of its source as an ability on the stack. Destruction or removal of the source after that time won\rquote t affect the ability. Note that some abilities cause a source to do something (for example, \ldblquote Prodigal Sorcerer deals 1 damage to target creature or player\rdblquote ) rather than the ability doing anything directly. In these cases, any activated or triggered ability that references information about the source because the effect needs to be divided checks that information when the ability is put onto the stack. Otherwise, it will check that information when it resolves. In both instances, if the source is no longer in play, its last known information is used. \par \par 402.7. An object may have multiple abilities. Aside from certain defined abilities that may be strung together on a single line (see rule 502, \ldblquote Keyword Abilities\rdblquote ), each paragraph break in a card\rquote s text marks a separate ability. An object may also have multiple instances of the same ability. Each instance functions independently. This may or may not produce more effects than a single instance; refer to the specific ability for more information.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK27}402.8. Abilities of an instant or sorcery usually function only while the object is on the stack. Abilities of all other objects usually function only while that object is in play. The exceptions are as follows:\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 402.8a Characteristic-defining abilities function in all zones. (See rule 405.2.)\par \par 402.8b An ability that states which zones it functions in functions only from those zones.\par \par 402.8c An ability of an object that modifies what it costs to play functions on the stack.\par \par 402.8d An object\rquote s ability that restricts or modifies how that object can be played functions in any zone from which it could be played.\par \par 402.8e An object\rquote s ability that modifies how it comes into play functions as that object is coming into play. See rule 419.6i.\par \par 402.8f An object\rquote s activated ability that has a cost that can\rquote t be paid while the object is in play functions from any zone in which its cost can be paid.\par \par 402.8g A trigger condition that can trigger only in a zone other than the in-play zone triggers from that zone. Other trigger conditions of the same triggered ability may function in different zones.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Absolver Thrull has the ability \ldblquote When Absolver Thrull comes into play or the creature it haunts is put into a graveyard, destroy target enchantment.\rdblquote  The first trigger condition triggers from the in-play zone and the second trigger condition functions from the removed-from-the-game zone. (See rule 502.51, \ldblquote Haunt.\rdblquote )\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 402.8h An ability whose cost or effect specifies that it moves the object it\rquote s on out of a particular zone functions only in that zone, unless that ability\rquote s trigger condition, or a previous part of that ability\rquote s cost or effect, specifies that the object is put into that zone.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Necrosavant says \ldblquote \{3\}\{B\}\{B\}, Sacrifice a creature: Return Necrosavant from your graveyard to play. Play this ability only during your upkeep.\rdblquote  A player may play this ability only if Necrosavant is in his or her graveyard.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK27}\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 403. Activated Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 403.1. An activated ability is written as \ldblquote [cost]: [effect].\rdblquote  The activation cost is everything before the colon (:). An ability\rquote s activation cost must be paid by the player who is playing it.\par \par 403.2. Only an object\rquote s controller (or its owner, if it doesn\rquote t have a controller) can play its activated ability unless the object specifically says otherwise.\par \par 403.3. If an activated ability has a restriction on its use (for example, \ldblquote Play this ability only once each turn\rdblquote ), the restriction continues to apply to that object even if its controller changes.\par \par 403.4. A creature\rquote s activated ability with the tap symbol (\{T\}) in its activation cost can\rquote t be played unless the creature has been under its controller\rquote s control since the start of his or her most recent turn. Ignore this rule for creatures with haste (see rule 502.5).\par \par 403.5. Activated abilities that read \ldblquote Play this ability only any time you could play a sorcery\rdblquote  mean the player must follow the timing rules for playing a sorcery spell, though the ability isn\rquote t actually a sorcery. Activated abilities that read \ldblquote Play this ability only any time you could play an instant\rdblquote  mean the player must follow the timing rules for playing an instant spell, though the ability isn\rquote t actually an instant.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 404. Triggered Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 404.1. A triggered ability begins with the word \ldblquote when,\rdblquote  \ldblquote whenever,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote at.\rdblquote  The phrase containing one of these words is the trigger condition, which defines the trigger event.\par \par 404.2. Triggered abilities aren\rquote t played. Instead, a triggered ability automatically \ldblquote triggers\rdblquote  each time its trigger event occurs. Once an ability has triggered, it goes on the stack the next time a player would receive priority. See rule 408.1, \ldblquote Timing, Priority, and the Stack,\rdblquote  and rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par 404.3. A triggered ability may read \ldblquote When/Whenever/At . . . , if [condition], [effect].\rdblquote  The ability checks for the stated condition to be true when the trigger event occurs. If it is, the ability triggers. On resolution, the ability rechecks the condition. If the condition isn\rquote t true at either of those times, the ability does nothing. This rule is referred to as the \ldblquote intervening \lquote if\rquote  clause\rdblquote  rule. Note that the word \ldblquote if\rdblquote  has only its normal English meaning anywhere else in the text of a card; this rule only applies to an \ldblquote if\rdblquote  that immediately follows a trigger condition.\par \par 404.4. An effect may create a delayed triggered ability that can do something at a later time. A delayed triggered ability will contain \ldblquote when,\rdblquote  \ldblquote whenever,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote at,\rdblquote  although that word won\rquote t usually begin the ability.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 404.4a Delayed triggered abilities come from spells or other abilities that create them on resolution. That means a delayed triggered ability won\rquote t trigger until it has actually been created, even if its trigger event occurred just beforehand. Other events that happen earlier may make the trigger event impossible.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Part of an effect reads \ldblquote When this creature leaves play,\rdblquote  but the creature in question leaves play before the spell or ability creating the effect resolves. In this case, the delayed ability never triggers.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If an effect reads \ldblquote When this creature becomes untapped\rdblquote  and the named creature becomes untapped before the effect resolves, the ability waits for the next time that creature untaps.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 404.4b A delayed triggered ability will trigger only once\emdash the next time its trigger event occurs\emdash unless it has a stated duration, such as \ldblquote this turn.\rdblquote \par \par 404.4c A delayed triggered ability that refers to a particular object still affects it even if the object changes characteristics.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An ability that reads \ldblquote Destroy that creature at end of turn\rdblquote  will destroy the permanent even if it\rquote s no longer a creature during the end of turn step.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 404.4d A delayed triggered ability that refers to a particular permanent will fail if the permanent leaves play (even if it returns again before the specified time). Similarly, abilities that create a one-shot effect that applies to an object in a particular zone will fail if the object leaves that zone.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An ability that reads \ldblquote Remove this creature from the game at end of turn\rdblquote  won\rquote t do anything if the creature leaves play before the end of turn step.}{\f0\insrsid3761202 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid12782545 404.4e}{\f0\insrsid3761202  The source of a delayed triggered ability created by a spell is that spell. The source of a delayed triggered ability created by another ability is the same as the source of that other ability.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid1259561  }{\f0\insrsid3761202 The controller of a delayed triggered ability is the same as the controller of the spell or ability that created it, even if that player no longer controls its source.\par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 404.5. Some objects have a static ability that\rquote s linked to a triggered ability. These objects combine both abilities into one paragraph, with the static ability first, followed by the triggered ability. A very few objects have triggered abilities which are written with the trigger condition in the middle of the ability, rather than at the beginning.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An ability that reads \ldblquote Reveal the first card you draw each turn. Whenever you reveal a basic land card this way, draw a card\rdblquote  is a static ability linked to a triggered ability.\par }\pard \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An ability that reads \ldblquote The controller of enchanted creature sacrifices it at the end of his or her turn\rdblquote  is a triggered ability.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 405. Static Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 405.1. A static ability does something all the time rather than being activated or triggered. The ability isn\rquote t played\emdash it just \ldblquote exists.\rdblquote  Such abilities apply only while the ability is on a permanent in play, unless the ability is covered by rule 402.8.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK28}405.2. Some objects have intrinsic static abilities }{\f0\insrsid3761202\delrsid471707\charrsid10638525 that define }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 the object\rquote s colors, subtypes, power, or toughness. These abilities are characteristic-defining abilities, and they function in all zones. Abilities of an object that affect the characteristics of another object are not characteristic-defining abilities. Neither are abilities that an object grants to itself, or abilities that set the values of such characteristics only if certain conditions are met. See rule 201, \ldblquote Characteristics,\rdblquote  and rule 418.5a.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK28}\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 406. Mana Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 406.1. A mana ability is either }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (a)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  an activated ability without a target that could put mana into a player\rquote s mana pool when it resolves or }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (b)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  a triggered ability without a target that triggers from a mana ability and could produce additional mana. A mana ability can generate other effects at the same time it produces mana.\par \par 406.2. Spells that put mana into a player\rquote s mana pool aren\rquote t mana abilities. They\rquote re played and resolved exactly like any other spells.\par \par 406.3. A mana ability remains a mana ability even if the game state doesn\rquote t allow it to produce mana.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A permanent has an ability that reads \ldblquote \{T\}: Add \{G\} to your mana pool for each creature you control.\rdblquote  This is still a mana ability even if you control no creatures or if the permanent is already tapped.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 406.4. A mana ability can be activated or triggered. Mana abilities are played and resolved like other abilities, but they don\rquote t go on the stack, so they can\rquote t be countered or responded to. See rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities,\rdblquote  and rule 408.2, \ldblquote Actions That Don\rquote t Use the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par 406.5. Abilities that produce mana but trigger from events other than playing mana abilities do use the stack. So do abilities that don\rquote t produce mana but trigger on playing mana abilities.\par \par 406.6. If a mana ability would produce one or more mana of an undefined type, it produces no mana instead.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If you control no lands, an ability that reads \ldblquote \{T\}: Add to your mana pool one mana of any type that a land you control could produce\rdblquote  will not produce any mana.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 407. Adding and Removing Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 407.1. Effects can add or remove abilities of objects. An effect that adds an ability will state that the object \ldblquote gains\rdblquote  or \ldblquote has\rdblquote  that ability. An effect that removes an ability will state that the object \ldblquote loses\rdblquote  that ability. If two or more effects add and remove the same ability, in general the most recent one prevails. (See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 407.2. An effect that sets an object\rquote s characteristic, or simply states a quality of that object, is different from an ability granted by an effect. When an object \ldblquote gains\rdblquote  or \ldblquote has\rdblquote  an ability, that ability can be removed by another effect. If an effect defines a characteristic of the object (\ldblquote [permanent] is [characteristic value]\rdblquote ), it\rquote s not granting an ability. (See rule 405.2.)\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An effect reads, \ldblquote Enchanted creature has \lquote This creature is an artifact creature.\rquote \rdblquote  This effect grants an ability to the creature that can be removed by other effects. Another effect reads, \ldblquote Enchanted creature is an artifact creature.\rdblquote  This effect simply defines a characteristic of the creature. It doesn\rquote t grant an ability, so effects that would cause the creature to lose its abilities wouldn\rquote t cause the enchanted creature to stop being an artifact.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 407.3. Effects that remove an ability remove all instances of it.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If a creature with flying is enchanted with Flight, it has two instances of the flying ability. A single effect that reads \ldblquote Target creature loses flying\rdblquote  will remove both.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 408. Timing of Spells and Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 408.1. Timing, Priority, and the Stack\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 408.1a Spells and activated abilities can be played only at certain times and follow a set of rules for doing so.\par \par 408.1b Spells and activated abilities are played by players (if they choose) using a system of priority, while other }{\f0\insrsid3761202 kind}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 s of abilities and effects are automatically generated by the game rules. Each time a player would get priority, all applicable state-based effects resolve first as a single event (see rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects\rdblquote ). Then, if any new state-based effects have been generated, they resolve as a single event. This process repeats until no more applicable state-based effects are generated. Then triggered abilities are added to the stack (see rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities\rdblquote ). These steps repeat in order until no further state-based effects or triggered abilities are generated. Then the player who would have received priority does so and may play a spell or ability, take a special action (such as playing a land), or pass, as governed by the rules for that phase or step.\par \par 408.1c The active player gets priority at the beginning of most phases and steps, after any game actions are dealt with and abilities that trigger at the beginning of that phase or step go on the stack. No player gets priority during the untap step and players usually don\rquote t get priority during the cleanup step (see rule 314.3). The player with priority may play a spell or ability, take a special action, or pass. If he or she plays a spell or ability, or takes a special action, the player again receives priority; otherwise, the next player in turn order receives priority. If all players pass in succession (that is, if all players pass without taking any actions in between passing), the top object on the stack resolves, then the active player receives priority. If the stack is empty when all players pass in succession, the phase or step ends and the next one begins.\par \par 408.1d A player may play an instant spell or an activated ability any time he or she has priority. Spells other than instants may be played during a player\rquote s main phase, when that player has priority and the stack is empty.\par \par 408.1e When a spell is played, it goes on top of the stack. When an activated ability is played, it goes on top of the stack.\par \par 408.1f Triggered abilities can trigger at any time, including during the playing or resolution of a spell or another ability. However, nothing actually happens at the time the abilities trigger. Each time a player would receive priority, each ability that has triggered is put on the stack (if it hasn\rquote t already been put on the stack). Then the player gets priority and may play spells or abilities. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 408.1g Combat damage goes on the stack once it\rquote s been assigned. For more information, see rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote \par \par 408.1h Static abilities aren\rquote t played\emdash they continuously affect the game. Priority doesn\rquote t apply to them. (See rule 405, \ldblquote Static Abilities,\rdblquote  rule 418, \ldblquote Continuous Effects,\rdblquote  and rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 408.1i Special actions don\rquote t use the stack. The special actions are playing a land (see rule 408.2d), turning a face-down creature face up (see rule 408.2h), ending continuous effects or stopping delayed triggered abilities (see rule 408.2i), ignoring continuous effects (see rule 408.2j), and removing a card with suspend in your hand from the game (see rule 408.2k).\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 408.2. Actions That Don\rquote t Use the Stack\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 408.2a Effects don\rquote t go on the stack; they\rquote re the result of spells and abilities resolving. Effects may create delayed triggered abilities, however, and these may go on the stack when they trigger (see rule 404.4).\par \par 408.2b Static abilities continuously generate effects and don\rquote t go on the stack.\par \par 408.2c State-based effects (see rule 420) resolve whenever a player would receive priority as long as the required game condition is true.\par \par }{\insrsid3761202\charrsid10123773 408.2d Playing a land is a special action consisting of putting that land into play. (See rule 212.6, \ldblquote Lands.\rdblquote ) A player can }{\insrsid3761202\charrsid5126621 choose to perform this special action only during a main phase of his or her turn, when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. If a player had priority before playing a land, that player gets priority after this special action.\par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 408.2e Mana abilities resolve immediately. If a mana ability produces both mana and another effect, both the mana and the other effect happen immediately. If a player had priority before a mana ability was played, that player gets priority after it resolves. (See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 408.2f Characteristic-defining abilities, such as \ldblquote [This object] is red,\rdblquote  are simply read and followed as applicable. (See also rule 405.2.)\par \par 408.2g Game actions don\rquote t use the stack. The game actions are phasing in and out at the start of the untap step (see rule 302.1), untapping at the start of the untap step (see rule 302.2), drawing a card at the start of the draw step (see rule 304.1), declaring attackers at the start of the declare attackers step (see rule 308.1), declaring blockers at the start of the declare blockers step (see rule 309.1), the active player discarding down to his or her maximum hand size at the start of the cleanup step (see rule 314.1), removing damage from permanents and ending \ldblquote until end of turn effects during the cleanup step (see rule 314.2), and mana burn as each phase ends (see rule 300.3).\par \par 408.2h The controller of a face-down permanent may turn it face up. This is a special action. (See rule 504, \ldblquote Face-Down Spells and Permanents.\rdblquote ) A player can turn a face-down permanent face up only when he or she has priority. That player gets priority after this special action.\par \par 408.2i Some effects allow a player to take an action at a later time, usually to end a continuous effect or to stop a delayed triggered ability. This is a special action. A player can end a continuous effect or stop a delayed triggered ability only if the effect or ability allows it and only when he or she has priority. The player who took the action gets priority after this special action.\par \par 408.2j Some effects from static abilities allow a player to take an action to ignore the effect from that ability for a duration. This is a special action. A player can take an action to ignore an effect only when he or she has priority. The player who took the action gets priority after this special action.\par \par 408.2k A player who has a card with suspend in his or her hand may remove that card from the game. This is a special action. (See rule 502.59, \ldblquote Suspend.\rdblquote ) A player can remove a card with suspend in his or her hand from the game only when he or she has priority. That player gets priority after this special action.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 409. Playing Spells and Activated Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 409.1. Playing a spell or activated ability follows the steps listed below, in order. If, at any point during the playing of a spell or ability, a player is unable to comply with any of the steps listed below, the spell was played illegally; the game returns to the moment before that spell or ability was played (see rule 422, \ldblquote Handling Illegal Actions\rdblquote ). Announcements and payments can\rquote t be altered after they\rquote ve been made.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 409.1a The player announces that he or she is playing the spell or activated ability. It moves from the zone it\rquote s in to the stack and remains there until it\rquote s countered or resolves. In the case of spells, the physical card goes onto the stack. In the case of activated abilities, the ability goes onto the stack without any card associated with it. If the ability is being played from a hidden zone, the card with that ability is revealed. Each spell has all the characteristics of the card associated with it. Each activated ability on the stack has the text of the ability that created it, and no other characteristics. The controller of a spell is the player who played the spell. The controller of an activated ability is the player who played the ability.\par \par 409.1b If the spell or ability is modal (uses the phrase \ldblquote Choose one \emdash }{\f0\insrsid3761202 ,}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \rdblquote  }{\f0\insrsid3761202 \ldblquote Choose two }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \emdash }{\f0\insrsid3761202 ,}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \rdblquote or \ldblquote [specified player] chooses one \emdash \rdblquote ), the player announces the mode choice. If the player wishes to splice any cards onto the spell (see rule 502.40), he or she reveals those cards in his or her hand. If the spell or ability has a variable mana cost (indicated by \{X\}) or some other variable cost, the player announces the value of that variable at this time. If the spell or ability has alternative, additional, or other special costs (such as buyback, kicker, or convoke costs), the player announces his or her intentions to pay any or all of those costs (see rule 409.1f). You can\rquote t apply two alternative methods of playing or two alternative costs to a single spell or ability. Previously made choices (such as choosing to play a spell with flashback from his or her graveyard or choosing to play a creature with morph face down) may restrict the player\rquote s options when making these choices.\par \par 409.1c If the spell or ability requires any targets, the player first announces how many targets he or she will choose (if the spell or ability has a variable number of targets), then announces the targets themselves. A player can\rquote t play a spell or ability unless he or she chooses the required number of legal targets. The same target can\rquote t be chosen multiple times for any one instance of the word \ldblquote target\rdblquote  on the spell or ability. If the spell or ability uses the word \ldblquote target\rdblquote  in multiple places, the same object, player, or zone can be chosen once for each instance of the word \ldblquote target\rdblquote  (as long as it fits the targeting criteria).\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If an ability reads \ldblquote Tap two target creatures,\rdblquote  then the same target can\rquote t be chosen twice; the ability requires two different legal targets. An ability that reads \ldblquote Destroy target artifact and target land,\rdblquote  however, can target the same artifact land twice because it uses the word \ldblquote target\rdblquote  in multiple places.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 409.1d If the spell or ability targets one or more targets only if an alternative, additional, or special cost (such as a buyback or kicker cost) is paid for it, or if a particular mode is chosen for it, its controller chooses those targets only if he or she announced the intention to pay that cost or chose that mode. Otherwise, the spell or ability is played as though it did not have those targets.\par \par 409.1e If the spell or ability affects several targets in different ways, the player announces how it will affect each target. If the spell or ability requires the player to divide or distribute an effect (such as damage or counters) among one or more targets, or any number of untargeted objects or players, the player announces the division. Each of these targets, objects, or players must receive at least one of whatever is being divided.\par \par 409.1f The player determines the total cost of the spell or ability. Usually this is just the mana cost (for spells) or activation cost (for abilities). Some cards list additional or alternative costs in their text. Some effects may increase or reduce the cost to pay, or may provide other alternative costs. Costs may include paying mana, tapping permanents, sacrificing permanents, discarding cards, and so on. The total cost is the mana cost, activation cost, or alternative cost, plus all additional costs and cost increases, and minus all cost reductions. If the mana component of the total cost is reduced to nothing by cost reduction effects, it is considered to be \{0\}. It can\rquote t be reduced to less than \{0\}. Once the total cost is determined, it becomes \ldblquote locked in.\rdblquote  If effects would change the total cost after this time, they have no effect.\par \par 409.1g If the total cost includes a mana payment, the player then has a chance to play mana abilities (see rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities\rdblquote ). Mana abilities must be played before costs are paid.\par \par 409.1h The player pays the total cost in any order. Partial payments are not allowed. Unpayable costs can\rquote t be paid.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  You play Death Bomb, which costs \{3\}\{B\} and has an additional cost of sacrificing a creature. You sacrifice Thunderscape Familiar, whose effect makes your black spells cost \{1\} less to play. Because a spell\rquote s total cost is \ldblquote locked in\rdblquote  before payments are actually made, you pay \{2\}\{B\}, not \{3\}\{B\}, even though you\rquote re sacrificing the Familiar.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 409.1i Once the steps described in 409.1a\endash h are completed, the spell or ability becomes played. Any abilities that trigger on a spell or ability being played or put onto the stack trigger at this time. If the spell or ability\rquote s controller had priority before playing it, he or she gets priority.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 409.2. Some spells and abilities specify that one of their controller\rquote s opponents does something the controller would normally do while it\rquote s being played, such as choose a mode, choose targets, or choose how the spell or ability will affect its targets. In these cases, the opponent does so when the spell or ability\rquote s controller normally would do so.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 409.2a If there is more than one opponent who could make such a choice, the spell or ability\rquote s controller decides which of those opponents will make the choice.\par \par 409.2b If the spell or ability instructs its controller and another player to do something at the same time as the spell or ability is being played, the spell\rquote s controller goes first, then the other player. This is an exception to rule 103.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 409.3. Playing a spell or ability that alters costs won\rquote t do anything to spells and abilities that are already on the stack.\par \par 409.4. A player can\rquote t begin to play a spell or activated ability that\rquote s prohibited from being played by an effect.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 409.4a If an effect allows a card that\rquote s prohibited from being played to be played face down, and the face-down spell would not be prohibited, that spell can be played face down. See rule 504, \ldblquote Face-Down Spells and Permanents.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 410. Handling Triggered Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 410.1. Because they aren\rquote t played, triggered abilities can trigger even when it isn\rquote t legal to play spells and abilities, and effects that prevent abilities from being played don\rquote t affect them.\par \par 410.2. Whenever a game event or game state matches a triggered ability\rquote s trigger event, that ability triggers. When a phase or step begins, all abilities that trigger \ldblquote at the beginning of\rdblquote  that phase or step trigger. The ability is controlled by the player who controlled its source at the time it triggered}{\f0\insrsid3761202 ,}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid8211582 unless it\rquote s a delayed triggered ability. The controller of a delayed triggered ability is the player who controlled the spell or ability that created it.}{\f0\insrsid3761202  }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 The ability doesn\rquote t do anything when it triggers, but it\rquote s automatically put on the stack by its controller as soon as a player would receive priority.}{\f0\insrsid3761202  Each triggered ability}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  }{\f0\insrsid3761202 on the stack }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 has the text of the ability that created it, and no other characteristics.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 410.2a If a triggered ability\rquote s trigger }{\f0\insrsid3761202 condition}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  is met, but the object with that triggered ability is at no time visible to all players, the ability does not trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 410.3. If multiple abilities have triggered since the last time a player received priority, each player, in APNAP order, puts triggered abilities he or she controls on the stack in any order he or she chooses. (See rule 103.4.) Then players once again check for and resolve state-based effects until none are generated, then abilities that triggered during this process go on the stack. This process repeats until no new state-based effects are generated and no abilities trigger. Then the appropriate player gets priority.\par \par 410.4. When a triggered ability goes on the stack, the controller of the ability makes any choices that would be required while playing an activated ability, following the same procedure (see rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities\rdblquote ). If no legal choice can be made (or if a rule or a continuous effect otherwise makes the ability illegal), the ability is simply removed from the stack.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 410.4a If a triggered ability is modal (that is, it uses the phrase \ldblquote Choose one \emdash \rdblquote  or \ldblquote [specified player] chooses one \emdash \rdblquote ), its controller announces the mode choice when he or she puts the ability on the stack. If one of the modes would be illegal to play (due to an inability to choose legal targets, for example), that mode can\rquote t be chosen. If no mode can be chosen, the ability is removed from the stack.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 410.5. Some triggered abilities\rquote  effects are optional (they contain \ldblquote may,\rdblquote  as in \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, you may draw a card\rdblquote ). These abilities go on the stack when they trigger, regardless of whether their controller intends to exercise the ability\rquote s option or not. The choice is made when the ability resolves. Likewise, triggered abilities that have an effect \ldblquote unless\rdblquote  something is true or a player chooses to do something will go on the stack normally; the \ldblquote unless\rdblquote  part of the ability is dealt with when the ability resolves.\par \par 410.6. An ability triggers only once each time its trigger event occurs. However, it can trigger repeatedly if one event contains multiple occurrences. See also rule 410.9.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A permanent has an ability whose trigger condition reads, \ldblquote Whenever a land is put into a graveyard from play, . . . .\rdblquote  If someone plays a spell that destroys all lands, the ability will trigger once for each land put into the graveyard during the spell\rquote s resolution.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 410.7. An ability triggers only if its trigger event actually occurs. An event that\rquote s prevented or replaced won\rquote t trigger anything.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An ability that triggers on damage being dealt won\rquote t trigger if all the damage is prevented.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK67}410.8. Triggered abilities with a condition directly following the trigger event (for example, \ldblquote When/Whenever/At [trigger], if [condition], [effect]\rdblquote ), check for the condition to be true as part of the trigger event; if it isn\rquote t, the ability doesn\rquote t trigger. The ability checks the condition again on resolution. If it\rquote s not satisfied, the ability does nothing. Note that this mirrors the check for legal targets. Note that this rule doesn\rquote t apply to any triggered ability with an \ldblquote if\rdblquote  condition elsewhere within its text. This rule is referred to as the \ldblquote intervening \lquote if\rquote  clause\rdblquote  rule.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK67}\par 410.9. Some abilities trigger when creatures block or are blocked in combat. (See rules 306\endash 311 and rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote ) They may trigger once or repeatedly, depending on the wording of the ability.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 410.9a An ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [this creature] blocks, . . .\rdblquote  triggers only once each combat for that creature, even if it blocks multiple creatures. It triggers only if the creature is declared as a blocker.\par \par 410.9b An ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [this creature] blocks a creature, . . .\rdblquote  triggers once for each attacking creature the creature with the ability blocks. It triggers only if the creature is declared as a blocker.\par \par 410.9c An ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [this creature] becomes blocked, . . .\rdblquote  triggers only once each combat for that creature, even if it\rquote s blocked by multiple creatures. It will also trigger if an effect causes a creature to block the attacking creature, but only if it hadn\rquote t already been blocked that combat. It will trigger if }{\f0\insrsid3761202\delrsid13632182\charrsid10638525 the creature}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  becomes blocked by an effect rather than a creature.\par \par 410.9d An ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever a creature blocks [this creature], . . .\rdblquote  triggers once for each creature that blocks the named creature. It will also trigger if an effect causes a creature to block the attacking creature, even if it had already been blocked that combat. It won\rquote t trigger if }{\f0\insrsid3761202\delrsid13632182\charrsid10638525 the creature}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  becomes blocked by an effect rather than a creature.\par \par 410.9e If an ability triggers when a creature blocks or becomes blocked by a particular number of creatures, the ability triggers if the creature blocks or is blocked by that many creatures when }{\f0\insrsid3761202 blockers are declared}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 . Effects that add or remove blockers can also cause such abilities to trigger. This applies to abilities that trigger on a creature blocking or being blocked by at least a certain number of creatures as well.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 410.10. Trigger events that involve objects changing zones are called \ldblquote zone-change triggers.\rdblquote  Many abilities with zone-change triggers attempt to do something to that object after it changes zones. During resolution, these abilities look for the object in the zone that it moved to. If the object is unable to be found in the zone it went to, the part of the ability attempting to do something to the object will fail to do anything. The ability could be unable to find the object because the object never entered the specified zone, because it left the zone before the ability resolved, or because it is in a zone that is hidden from a player, such as a library or an opponent\rquote s hand. (This rule applies even if the object leaves the zone and returns again before the ability resolves.) The most common zone-change triggers are comes-into-play triggers and leaves-play triggers.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 410.10a Comes-into-play abilities trigger when a permanent enters the in-play zone. These are written, \ldblquote When [this object] comes into play, . . . \ldblquote  or \ldblquote Whenever a [type] comes into play, . . .\rdblquote  Each time an event puts one or more permanents into play, all permanents in play (including the newcomers) are checked for any comes-into-play triggers that match the event.\par \par 410.10b Continuous effects that modify characteristics of a permanent do so the moment the permanent is in play (and not before then). The permanent is never in play with its unmodified characteristics. Continuous effects don\rquote t apply before the permanent is in play, however (see rule 410.10e).\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If an effect reads \ldblquote All lands are creatures\rdblquote  and a land card is played, the effect makes the land card into a creature the moment it enters play, so it would trigger abilities that trigger when a creature comes into play. Conversely, if an effect reads \ldblquote All creatures lose all abilities\rdblquote  and a creature card with a comes-into-play triggered ability enters play, that effect will cause it to lose its abilities the moment it enters play, so the comes-into-play ability won\rquote t trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 410.10c Leaves-play abilities trigger when a permanent leaves the in-play zone. These are written as, but aren\rquote t limited to, \ldblquote When [this object] leaves play, . . .\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Whenever [something] is put into a graveyard from play, . . . .\rdblquote  An ability that attempts to do something to the card that left play checks for it only in the first zone that it went to.\par \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 410.10d Normally, objects that exist immediately after an event }{\f0\insrsid3761202\delrsid4140491\charrsid10638525 are checked to see if the event matched any trigger conditions}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 . Continuous effects that exist at that time are used to determine what the trigger conditions are and what the objects involved in the event look like. However, some triggered abilities must be treated specially because the object with the ability may no longer be in play, }{\f0\insrsid3761202\delrsid12742312\charrsid10638525 may }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 have moved to a hand or library, or may no longer be controlled by the appropriate player. The game has to \ldblquote look back in time\rdblquote  to determine if these abilities trigger. Abilities that trigger specifically when an object leaves play, when an object is put into a hand or library, or when a player loses control of an object will trigger based on their existence, and the appearance of objects, prior to the event rather than afterward.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Two creatures are in play along with an artifact that has the ability \ldblquote Whenever a creature is put into a graveyard from play, you gain 1 life.\rdblquote  Someone plays a spell that destroys all artifacts, creatures, and enchantments. The artifact\rquote s ability triggers twice, even though the artifact goes to its owner\rquote s graveyard at the same time as the creatures.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK66}410.10e Some permanents have text that reads \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play with . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote As [this permanent] comes into play . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play as . . . ,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play tapped.\rdblquote  Such text is a static ability\emdash not a triggered ability\emdash whose effect occurs as part of the event that puts the permanent into play.\par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK66}\par 410.10f Some Auras have triggered abilities that trigger on the enchanted permanent leaving play. These triggered abilities can track the Aura to its owner\rquote s graveyard in addition to tracking the enchanted permanent to whatever zone it moved to.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 410.11. Some triggered abilities trigger on a game state, such as a player controlling no permanents of a particular }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type, rather than triggering when an event occurs. These abilities trigger as soon as the game state matches the condition. They\rquote ll go onto the stack at the next available opportunity. These are called state triggers. (Note that state triggers aren\rquote t the same as state-based effects.) A state-triggered ability doesn\rquote t trigger again until the ability has resolved, has been countered, or has otherwise left the stack. Then, if the object with the ability is still in the same zone and the game state still matches its trigger condition, the ability will trigger again.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A permanent\rquote s ability reads, \ldblquote Whenever you have no cards in hand, draw a card.\rdblquote  If its controller plays the last card from his or her hand, the ability will trigger once and won\rquote t trigger again until it has resolved. If its controller plays a spell that reads \ldblquote Discard your hand, then draw that many cards,\rdblquote  the ability will trigger during the spell\rquote s resolution because the player\rquote s hand was momentarily empty.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 411. Playing Mana Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 411.1. To play a mana ability, the player announces that he or she is playing it and pays the activation cost, following the steps in rules 409.1b\endash i. It resolves immediately after it is played and doesn\rquote t go on the stack. (See rule 408.2e.)\par \par 411.2. A player may play an activated mana ability whenever he or she has priority, or whenever he or she is playing a spell or activated ability that requires a mana payment. A player may also play one whenever a rule or effect asks for a mana payment, even in the middle of playing or resolving a spell or ability.\par \par 411.3. Triggered mana abilities trigger when an activated mana ability is played. These abilities resolve immediately after the mana ability that triggered them, without waiting for priority. If an activated or triggered ability produces both mana and another effect, both the mana and the other effect resolve immediately.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An enchantment reads, \ldblquote }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Whenever a player taps a land for mana, that player adds one mana of that type to his or her mana pool}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 .\rdblquote  If a player taps lands for mana while playing a spell, the additional mana is added to the player\rquote s mana pool immediately and can be used to pay for the spell.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 411.3a If a triggered mana ability adds mana \ldblquote of the same type\rdblquote  or \ldblquote of the same color\rdblquote  to a player\rquote s mana pool and the mana ability that triggered it produced more than one type or color of mana, the player to whose mana pool the mana is being added chooses which type or color of mana the triggered ability adds.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 412. Handling Static Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 412.1. A static ability may generate a continuous effect or a prevention or replacement effect. These effects last as long as the object with the static ability remains in the appropriate zone.\par \par 412.2. Many Auras, Equipment, and Fortifications have static abilities that modify the object they\rquote re attached to, but those abilities don\rquote t target that object. If an Aura, Equipment, or Fortification is moved to a different object, the ability stops applying to the original object and starts modifying the new one.\par \par 412.3. Some static abilities apply while a spell is on the stack. These are often abilities that refer to countering the spell. Also, abilities that say \ldblquote As an additional cost to play . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote You may pay [cost] rather than pay [this object]\rquote s mana cost,\rdblquote  and \ldblquote You may play [this object] without paying its mana cost\rdblquote  work while a spell is on the stack.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK29}412.4. Some static abilities apply while a card is in any zone that you could play it from (usually your hand). These are limited to those that read, \ldblquote You may play [this card] . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote You can\rquote t play [this card] . . . ,\rdblquote  and \ldblquote Play [this card] only . . . .\rdblquote \par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK29}\par 412.5. Unlike spells and other kinds of abilities, static abilities can\rquote t use an object\rquote s last known information for purposes of determining how their effects are applied.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 413. Resolving Spells and Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 413.1. Each time all players pass in succession, the object (a spell, an ability, or combat damage) on top of the stack resolves. (See rule 416, \ldblquote Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 413.2. Resolution of a spell or ability may involve several steps. These steps are followed in the order listed below.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 413.2a If the spell or ability specifies targets, it checks whether the targets are still legal. A target that\rquote s moved out of the zone it was in when it was targeted is illegal. Other changes to the game state may cause a target to no longer be legal; for example, its characteristics may have changed or an effect may have changed the text of the spell. If the source of an ability has left the zone it was in, its last known information is used during this process to determine its characteristics. The spell or ability is countered if all its targets, for every instance of the word \ldblquote target,\rdblquote  are now illegal. If the spell or ability is not countered, it will resolve normally, affecting only the targets that are still legal. If a target is illegal, the spell or ability can\rquote t perform any actions on it or make the target perform any actions.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Aura Blast is a white instant that reads, \ldblquote Destroy target enchantment. Draw a card.\rdblquote  If the enchantment isn\rquote t a legal target during Aura Blast\rquote s resolution (say, if it has gained protection from white or left play), then Aura Blast is countered. Its controller doesn\rquote t draw a card.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example: }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Plague Spores reads, \ldblquote Destroy target nonblack creature and target land. They can\rquote t be regenerated.\rdblquote  Suppose the same animated land is chosen both as the nonblack creature and as the land, and the color of the creature land is changed to black before Plague Spores resolves. Plagues Spores isn\rquote t countered because the black creature land is still a legal target for the \ldblquote target land\rdblquote  part of the spell.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 413.2b The controller of the spell or ability follows its instructions in the order written. However, replacement effects may modify these actions. In some cases, later text on the card may modify the meaning of earlier text (for example, \ldblquote Destroy target creature. It can\rquote t be regenerated\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Counter target spell. If that spell is countered this way, put it on top of its owner\rquote s library instead of into its owner\rquote s graveyard.\rdblquote ) Don\rquote t just apply effects step by step without thinking in these cases\emdash read the whole text and apply the rules of English to the text.\par \par 413.2c If an effect offers any choices other than choices already made as part of playing the spell or ability, the player announces these while applying the effect. The player can\rquote t choose an option that\rquote s illegal or impossible. (For example, a player can\rquote t avoid the consequences of not taking an optional action if he or she can\rquote t meet all the immediate requirements of that action.) Drawing a card is never considered an impossible action, even if there are no cards in the affected player's library.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A spell\rquote s instruction reads, \ldblquote You may sacrifice a creature. If you don\rquote t, you lose 4 life.\rdblquote  A player who controls no creatures can\rquote t choose the sacrifice option.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 413.2d Some spells and abilities have multiple steps or actions, denoted by separate sentences or clauses, that involve multiple players. In these cases, the choices for the first action are made in APNAP order, and then the first action is processed simultaneously. Then the choices for the second action are made in APNAP order, and then that action is processed simultaneously, and so on. See rule 103.4.\par \par 413.2e If an effect gives a player the option to pay mana, he or she may play mana abilities before taking that action. If an effect specifically instructs or allows a player to play a spell during resolution, he or she does so by putting that spell on top of the stack, then continuing to play it by following the steps in rules 409.1a\endash i, except no player receives priority after it\rquote s played. The currently resolving spell or ability then continues to resolve, which may include playing other spells this way. No other spells or abilities can normally be played during resolution.\par \par 413.2f If an effect requires information from the game (such as the number of creatures in play), the answer is determined only once, when the effect is applied. If the effect requires information from a specific object, including the source of the ability itself, the effect uses the current information of that object if it hasn\rquote t changed zones; otherwise, the effect uses the last known information the object had before leaving the zone it was expected to be in. There are two exceptions: (1) if an effect deals damage divided among some number of creatures or players, the amount and division were determined as the spell or ability was put into the stack (see rule 402.6), and (2) static abilities can\rquote t use last known information (see rule 412.5). If the ability text states that an object does something, it\rquote s the object as it exists\emdash or as it most recently existed\emdash that does it, not the ability.\par \par 413.2g If an effect refers to certain characteristics, it checks only for the value of the specified characteristics, regardless of any related ones an object may also have.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An effect that reads \ldblquote Destroy all black creatures\rdblquote  destroys a white-and-black creature, but one that reads \ldblquote Destroy all nonblack creatures\rdblquote  doesn\rquote t.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 413.2h If an ability\rquote s effect refers to a specific untargeted object that has been previously referred to by that ability\rquote s cost or trigger condition, it still affects that object even if the object has changed characteristics.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Wall of Tears says \ldblquote Whenever Wall of Tears blocks a creature, return that creature to its owner\rquote s hand at end of combat.\rdblquote  If Wall of Tears blocks a creature, then that creature ceases to be a creature before the triggered ability resolves, the permanent will still be returned to its owner\rquote s hand.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 413.2i A spell is put into play from the stack under the control of the spell\rquote s controller (for permanents) or is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard from the stack (for instants and sorceries) as the final step of the spell\rquote s resolution.}{\f0\insrsid3761202  An ability is removed from the stack and ceases to exist as the final step of its resolution.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par \par 413.2j If an effect could result in a tie, the text of the spell or ability that created the effect will specify what to do in the event of a tie. The }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  game has no default for ties.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 414. Countering Spells and Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 414.1. To counter a spell is to move the spell from the stack to its owner\rquote s graveyard. Countering an ability removes it from the stack. Spells and abilities that are countered don\rquote t resolve and none of their effects occur.\par \par 414.2. The player who played the countered spell or ability doesn\rquote t get a \ldblquote refund\rdblquote  of any costs that were paid.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 415. Targeted Spells and Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 415.1. An instant or sorcery spell is targeted if the text that will be followed when it resolves uses the phrase \ldblquote target [something],\rdblquote  where the \ldblquote something\rdblquote  is a phrase that describes an object, player, or zone. (If an activated or triggered ability of an instant or sorcery uses the word target, that ability is targeted, but the spell is not.)\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A sorcery card has the ability \ldblquote When you cycle this card, target creature gets -1/-1 until end of turn.\rdblquote  This triggered ability is targeted, but that doesn\rquote t make the card it\rquote s on targeted.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 415.2. An activated or triggered ability is targeted if it uses the phrase \ldblquote target [something],\rdblquote  where the \ldblquote something\rdblquote  is a phrase that describes an object, player, or zone.\par \par 415.3. Aura spells are always targeted. An Aura\rquote s target is specified by its enchant keyword ability (see rule 502.45, \ldblquote Enchant\rdblquote ). An Aura permanent doesn\rquote t target anything; only the spell is targeted. An activated or triggered ability of an Aura permanent can be targeted.\par           Neither Equipment spells nor Equipment permanents target anything. The equip ability is targeted; see rule 502.33, \ldblquote Equip.\rdblquote  An activated or triggered ability of an Equipment permanent can be targeted.\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525           Neither Fortification spells nor Fortification permanents target anything. The fortify ability is targeted; see rule 502.65, \ldblquote Fortify.\rdblquote  An activated or triggered ability of a Fortification permanent can be targeted.\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 415.4. Spells and abilities that can have zero or more targets are targeted only if one or more targets have been chosen for them.\par \par 415.5. Only permanents are legal targets for spells and abilities, unless a spell or ability }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (a)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  specifies that it can target an object in another zone or a player or }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (b)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  targets an object that can\rquote t exist in the in-play zone, such as a spell or ability.\par \par 415.6. A spell or ability on the stack is an illegal target for itself.\par \par 415.7. Changing Targets\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 415.7a The target of a spell or ability can change only to another legal target. If the target can\rquote t be changed to another legal target, the original target is unchanged.\par \par 415.7b Modal spells and abilities may have different targeting requirements for each mode. Changing a spell or ability\rquote s target can\rquote t change its mode.\par \par 415.7c The word \ldblquote you\rdblquote  in an object\rquote s text isn\rquote t a target.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 416. Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 416.1. When a spell or ability resolves, it may create one or more one-shot or continuous effects. Static abilities may create one or more continuous effects. Some effects are replacement effects or prevention effects. State-based effects are not created by spells or abilities; they are generated by specific rules of the game (see rule 420).\par \par 416.2. Effects apply only to permanents unless the instruction\rquote s text states otherwise or they clearly can apply only to objects in one or more other zones.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An effect that changes all lands into creatures won\rquote t alter land cards in players\rquote  graveyards. But an effect that says spells cost more to play will apply only to spells on the stack, since a spell is always on the stack while you are playing it.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 416.3. If an effect attempts to do something impossible, it does only as much as possible.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If a player is holding only one card, an effect that reads \ldblquote Discard two cards\rdblquote  causes him or her to discard only that card. If an effect moves cards out of the library (as opposed to drawing), it moves as many as possible.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 417. One-Shot Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 417.1. A one-shot effect does something just once and doesn\rquote t have a duration. Examples include damage dealing, destruction of permanents, and moving objects between zones.\par \par 417.2. Some one-shot effects instruct a player to do something later in the game (usually at a specific time) rather than when they resolve. This kind of effect actually creates a new ability that waits to be triggered. (See rule 404.4.)\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 418. Continuous Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.1. A continuous effect modifies characteristics of objects, modifies control of objects, or affects players or the rules of the game, for a fixed or indefinite period. A continuous effect may be generated by the resolution of a spell or ability or by a static ability of an object.\par \par 418.2. Continuous effects that modify characteristics of permanents do so simultaneously with the permanent coming into play. They don\rquote t wait until the permanent is in play and then change it. Because such effects apply as the permanent comes into play, apply them before determining whether the permanent will cause an ability to trigger when it comes into play.\par \par 418.3. Continuous Effects from Spells or Abilities\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 418.3a A continuous effect generated by the resolution of a spell or ability lasts as long as stated by the spell or ability creating it (such as \ldblquote until end of turn\rdblquote ). If no duration is stated, it lasts until the end of the game.\par \par 418.3b The set of objects that are affected by continuous effects from spells, activated abilities, and triggered abilities that modify the characteristics or change the controller of those objects is determined when that continuous effect begins. After that point, the set won\rquote t change. Note that these work differently than continuous effects from static abilities. Continuous effects that don\rquote t modify characteristics or change the controller of objects modify the rules of the game, so they can affect objects that weren\rquote t affected when the continuous effect began.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An effect that reads \ldblquote All white creatures get +1/+1 until end of turn\rdblquote  gives the bonus to all permanents that are white creatures when the spell or ability resolves\emdash even if they change color later\emdash and doesn\rquote t affect those that come into play or turn white afterward.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An effect that reads \ldblquote Prevent all damage creatures would deal this turn\rdblquote  doesn\rquote t modify any object\rquote s characteristics, so it\rquote s modifying the rules of the game. That means the effect will apply even to damage from creatures that weren\rquote t in play when the continuous effect began. It also affects damage from permanents that become creatures later in the turn.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.3c If a resolving spell or ability that creates a continuous effect contains a variable, the value of that variable is determined only once, on resolution. See rule 413.2f.\par \par 418.3d Some effects from activated or triggered abilities have durations worded \ldblquote as long as . . . .\rdblquote  If the \ldblquote as long as\rdblquote  duration ends between the end of playing the activated ability or putting the triggered ability onto the stack and the moment when the effect would first be applied, the effect does nothing. It doesn\rquote t start and immediately stop again, and it doesn\rquote t last forever.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Endoskeleton is an artifact with an activated ability that reads \ldblquote \{2\}, \{T\}: Target creature gets +0/+3 as long as Endoskeleton remains tapped.\rdblquote  If you play this ability and then Endoskeleton becomes untapped before the ability resolves, it does nothing, because its duration\emdash remaining tapped\emdash was over before the effect began.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.4. Continuous Effects from Static Abilities\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 418.4a A continuous effect generated by a static ability isn\rquote t \ldblquote locked in\rdblquote ; it applies at any given moment to whatever its text indicates.\par \par 418.4b The effect applies at all times that the permanent generating it is in play or the object generating it is in the appropriate zone.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A permanent with the static ability \ldblquote All white creatures get +1/+1\rdblquote  generates an effect that continuously gives +1/+1 to each white creature in play. If a creature becomes white, it gets this bonus; a creature that stops being white loses it. A creature spell that would normally create a 1/1 white creature instead creates a 2/2 white creature. The creature doesn\rquote t come into play as 1/1 and then change to 2/2.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.5. Interaction of Continuous Effects\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.5a The values of an object\rquote s characteristics are determined by starting with the actual object, then applying continuous effects in a series of layers in the following order: (1) copy effects (see rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects\rdblquote ); (2) control-changing effects; (3) text-changing effects; (4)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid291000  }{\f0\insrsid3761202 type-changing effects (which includes effects that change an object\rquote s card}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  type, subtype, and}{\f0\insrsid3761202 /or}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  supertype}{\f0\insrsid3761202 )}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 ; (5) all other continuous effects, except those that change power and/or toughness; and (6) power- and/or toughness-changing effects.\par           Inside each layer from 1 through 5, apply effects from characteristic-defining abilities first, then all other effects in timestamp order. Inside layer 6, apply effects in a series of sublayers in the following order: (6a) effects from characteristic-}{\f0\insrsid3761202 defining}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  abilities; (6b) all other effects not specifically applied in 6c, 6d, or 6e; (6c) changes from counters; (6d) effects from static abilities that modify power and/or toughness but don\rquote t set power and/or toughness to a specific number or value; and (6e) effects that switch a creature\rquote s power and toughness. Within each sublayer, apply effects in timestamp order. Note that dependency may alter the order in which effects are applied within a layer or sublayer. See also the rules for timestamp order and dependency (rules 418.5b\endash 418.5g).\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Crusade is an enchantment that reads \ldblquote White creatures get +1/+1.\rdblquote  Crusade and a 2/2 black creature are in play. If an effect then turns the creature white (layer 5), it gets +1/+1 from Crusade (layer 6d), becoming 3/3. If the creature\rquote s color is later changed to red (layer 5), Crusade\rquote s effect stops applying to it, and it will return to being a 2/2.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Gray Ogre, a 2/2 creature, is in play. An effect puts a +1/+1 counter on it (layer 6c), making it 3/3. An effect that says \ldblquote Target creature gets +4/+4 until end of turn\rdblquote  is applied to it (layer 6b), making it 7/7. An enchantment that says \ldblquote Creatures you control get +0/+2\rdblquote  enters play (layer 6d), making it a 7/9. An effect that says \ldblquote Target creature becomes 0/1 until end of turn\rdblquote  is applied to it (layer 6b), making it a 1/4 (0/1, plus +1/+1 from the counter, plus +0/+2 from the enchantment).}{\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f24\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.5b If an effect should be applied in different layers, the parts of the effect each apply in their appropriate layers. If an effect starts to apply in one layer, it will continue to be applied to the same set of objects in each other applicable layer, even if the ability generating the effect is removed during this process.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An effect that reads \ldblquote Wild Mongrel gets +1/+1 and becomes the color of your choice until end of turn\rdblquote  is both a power- and toughness-changing effect and an \ldblquote other\rdblquote  kind of effect. The \ldblquote becomes the color of your choice\rdblquote  part is applied in layer 5, and then the \ldblquote gets +1/+1\rdblquote  part is applied in layer 6.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Grab the Reins has an effect that reads \ldblquote Until end of turn, you gain control of target creature and it gains haste.\rdblquote  This is both a control-changing effect and an \ldblquote other\rdblquote  effect. The \ldblquote you gain control\rdblquote  part is applied in layer 2, and then the \ldblquote it gains haste\rdblquote  part is applied in layer 5.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  An effect that reads \ldblquote All noncreature artifacts become 2/2 artifact creatures until end of turn\rdblquote  is both a type-changing effect and a power- and toughness-setting effect. The type-changing effect is applied to all noncreature artifacts in layer 4 and the power- and toughness-setting effect is applied to those same permanents in layer 6, even though those permanents aren\rquote t noncreature artifacts by then.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Svogthos, the Restless Tomb, is in play. An effect that says \ldblquote }{\f0\cf1\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Until end of turn, target land becomes a 3/3 creature that\rquote s still a land}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \rdblquote  is applied to it (layers 4 and 6b). An effect that says \ldblquote Target creature gets +1/+1 until end of turn\rdblquote  is applied to it (layer 6b), making it a 4/4 land creature. Then you activate Svogthos\rquote s ability (\ldblquote }{\f0\cf1\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Until end of turn, Svogthos, the Restless Tomb becomes a black and green Plant Zombie creature with \lquote This creature\rquote s power and toughness are each equal to the number of creature cards in your graveyard.\rquote  It\rquote s still a land.\rdblquote )}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  while you have ten creature cards in your graveyard (layers 4, 5, and 6b). It becomes a 10/10 land creature. If a creature card enters or leaves your graveyard, Svogthos\rquote s power and toughness will be modified accordingly. If the first effect is applied to it again, it will become a 3/3 land creature again.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 418.5c An effect is said to \ldblquote depend on\rdblquote  another if }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (a) }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 it\rquote s applied in the same layer (and, if applicable, sublayer) as the other effect (see rule 418.5a); }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (b) }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 applying the other would change the text or the existence of the first effect, what it applies to, or what it does to any of the things it applies to;}{\f0\insrsid3761202\delrsid471707\charrsid10638525  and }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\delrsid471707\charrsid10638525 (c)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\delrsid471707\charrsid10638525  neither effect is from a characteristic-defining ability.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Otherwise, the effect is considered to be independent of the other effect.\par \par 418.5d An effect dependent on one or more other effects waits to apply until just after all of those effects have been applied. If multiple dependent effects would apply simultaneously in this way, they\rquote re applied in \ldblquote timestamp order\rdblquote  relative to each other. If several dependent effects form a dependency loop, then this rule is ignored and the effects in the dependency loop are applied in timestamp order.\par \par 418.5e An object\rquote s timestamp is the time it entered the zone it\rquote s currently in, with three exceptions: }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (a)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If two or more objects enter a zone (or zones) simultaneously, the active player determines their timestamp order at the time they enter that zone. }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (b)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Whenever an Aura, Equipment, or Fortification becomes attached to an object or player, the Aura, Equipment, or Fortification receives a new timestamp. }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (c)}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Permanents that phase in keep the same timestamps they had when they phased out.\par \par 418.5f A continuous effect generated by a static ability has the same timestamp as the object the static ability is on, or the timestamp of the effect that created the ability, whichever is later.\par \par 418.5g A continuous effect generated by the resolution of a spell or ability receives a timestamp at the time it\rquote s created.\par \par 418.5h One continuous effect can override another. Sometimes the results of one effect determine whether another effect applies or what another effect does.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Two Auras are played on the same creature: \ldblquote Enchanted creature gains flying\rdblquote  and \ldblquote Enchanted creature loses flying.\rdblquote  Neither of these depends on the other, since nothing changes what they affect or what they\rquote re doing to it. Applying them in timestamp order means the one that was generated last \ldblquote wins.\rdblquote  It\rquote s irrelevant whether an effect is temporary (such as \ldblquote Target creature loses flying until end of turn\rdblquote ) or global (such as \ldblquote All creatures lose flying\rdblquote ).\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  One effect reads, \ldblquote White creatures get +1/+1,\rdblquote  and another, \ldblquote Enchanted creature is white.\rdblquote  The enchanted creature gets +1/+1 from the first effect, regardless of its previous color.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.5i Some effects switch a creature\rquote s power and toughness. When they\rquote re applied, they take the value of power and apply it to the object\rquote s toughness, and take the object\rquote s toughness and apply it to the object\rquote s power. These effects are applied after all other effects that affect power and toughness. (See rule 418.5a.)\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A 1/3 creature is given +0/+1 by an effect. Then another effect switches the creature\rquote s power and toughness. Its new power and toughness is 4/1. A new effect gives the creature +5/+0. Its \ldblquote unswitched\rdblquote  power and toughness would be 6/4, so its actual power and toughness is 4/6.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A 1/3 creature is given +0/+1 by an effect. Then another effect switches the creature\rquote s power and toughness. Its new power and toughness is 4/1. If the +0/+1 effect ends before the switch effect ends, the creature becomes a 3/1.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 418.5j Some continuous effects affect players rather than objects. For example, an effect might give a player protection from red. All such effects are applied in timestamp order after the determination of objects\rquote  characteristics. See also the rules for timestamp order and dependency (rules 418.5b\endash 418.5g).\par \par 418.5k Some continuous effects affect game rules rather than objects. For example, effects may modify a player\rquote s maximum hand size. These effects are applied after all other continuous effects have been applied. Continuous effects that affect the costs of spells or abilities are applied according to the order specified in rule 4}{\f0\insrsid3761202 0}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 9.1f. All other such effects are applied in timestamp order. See also the rules for timestamp order and dependency (rules 418.5b\endash g).\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.6. Text-Changing Effects\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 418.6a An effect that changes the text of an object changes only those words that are used in the correct way (for example, a }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  color word being used as a color word, a land type word used as a land type, or a creature type word used as a creature type). The effect can\rquote t change a proper noun, such as a card name, even if that proper noun contains a word or a series of letters that is the same as a }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  color word, basic land type, or creature type.\par \par 418.6b Effects that add or remove abilities don\rquote t change the text of the objects they affect, so any abilities that are granted to an object can\rquote t be changed by effects that change the text of that object.\par \par 418.6c }{\f0\insrsid3761202 Most s}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 pells and abilities that create creature tokens use creature types to define both the creature types and the names of the tokens. These words can be changed, because they are being used as creature types, even though they\rquote re also being used as names.\par \par 418.6d A creature token\rquote s creature type and rules text are defined by the spell or ability that created the token. These characteristics can be changed by text-changing effects.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419. Replacement and Prevention Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.1. Replacement and prevention effects are continuous effects that watch for a particular event to happen and then completely or partially replace that event. These effects act like \ldblquote shields\rdblquote  around whatever they\rquote re affecting.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.1a Effects that use the word \ldblquote instead\rdblquote  are replacement effects. Most replacement effects use the word \ldblquote instead\rdblquote  to indicate what events will be replaced with other events and use the word \ldblquote skip\rdblquote  to indicate what events, steps, phases, or turns will be replaced with nothing.\par \par 419.1b Effects that read \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play with . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote As [this permanent] comes into play . . . ,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play as . . . \rdblquote  are replacement effects.\par \par 419.1c Continuous effects that read \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play . . .\rdblquote  or \ldblquote [Objects] come into play . . .\rdblquote  are replacement effects.\par \par 419.1d Effects that use the word \ldblquote prevent\rdblquote  are prevention effects. Prevention effects use \ldblquote prevent\rdblquote  to indicate what events will not occur.\par \par 419.1e Effects that read \ldblquote As [this permanent] is turned face up . . . ,\rdblquote  are replacement effects.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.2. Replacement and prevention effects apply continuously as events happen\emdash they aren\rquote t locked in ahead of time.\par \par 419.3. There are no special restrictions on playing a spell or ability that generates a replacement or prevention effect. Such effects last until they\rquote re used up or their duration has expired.\par \par 419.4. Replacement or prevention effects must exist before the appropriate event occurs\emdash they can\rquote t \ldblquote go back in time\rdblquote  and change something that\rquote s already happened. Usually spells and abilities that generate these effects are played in response to whatever would produce the event and thus resolve before that event would occur.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A player can play a regeneration ability in response to a spell that would destroy a creature he or she controls.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.5. If an event is prevented or replaced, it never happens. A modified event occurs instead, which may in turn trigger abilities. Note that the modified event may contain instructions that can\rquote t be carried out, in which case the player simply ignores the impossible instruction.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.5a If a source would deal 0 damage, it does not deal damage at all. That means abilities that trigger on damage being dealt won\rquote t trigger. It also means that replacement effects that increase damage dealt have no event to replace, so they have no effect.\par \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.5b Some abilities read, \ldblquote you may [X]. If you do, [Y].\rdblquote  An \ldblquote if you do\rdblquote  clause that follows a \ldblquote you may [X]\rdblquote  clause refers to choosing to do the event X, regardless of what events actually occur as a result of that decision. If X is replaced entirely or in part by a different event, the \ldblquote if you do\rdblquote  clause refers to the event that replaced X.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.6. Replacement Effects\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.6a A replacement effect doesn\rquote t invoke itself repeatedly and gets only one opportunity for each event.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A player controls two permanents, each with an ability that reads \ldblquote If a creature you control would deal damage to a creature or player, it deals double that damage to that creature or player instead.\rdblquote  A creature that normally deals 2 damage will deal 8 damage\emdash not just 4, and not an infinite amount.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.6b Regeneration is a destruction-replacement effect. The word \ldblquote instead\rdblquote  doesn\rquote t appear on the card but is implicit in the definition of regeneration. \ldblquote Regenerate [permanent]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote The next time [permanent] would be destroyed this turn, instead remove all damage from it, tap it, and (if it\rquote s in combat) remove it from combat.\rdblquote  Abilities that trigger from damage being dealt still trigger even if the permanent regenerates.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK68}419.6c Some effects replace damage dealt to one creature}{\f0\insrsid3761202 , planeswalker,}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  or player with the same damage dealt to another creature}{\f0\insrsid3761202 , planeswalker,}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  or player; such effects are called \ldblquote redirection\rdblquote  effects. If either creature }{\f0\insrsid3761202 or planewalker }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 is no longer in play}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid8457758  }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 when the damage would be redirected}{\f0\insrsid3761202 ,}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  or is no longer a creature }{\f0\insrsid3761202 or planeswalker }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 when the damage would be redirected, the effect does nothing.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK68}\par 419.6d Some spells and abilities replace part or all of their own effect(s) when they resolve. Such effects are called }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 self-replacement effects}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 . When applying replacement effects to an event, apply self-replacement effects first, then apply other replacement effects.\par \par 419.6e Skipping an action, step, phase, or turn is a replacement effect. \ldblquote Skip [something]\rdblquote  is the same as \ldblquote Instead of doing [something], do nothing.\rdblquote  Once a step, phase, or turn has started, it can no longer be skipped\emdash any skip effects will wait until the next occurrence.\par \par 419.6f Anything scheduled for a skipped step, phase, or turn won\rquote t happen. Anything scheduled for the \ldblquote next\rdblquote  occurrence of something waits for the first occurrence that isn\rquote t skipped. If two effects each cause a player to skip his or her next occurrence, that player must skip the next two; one effect will be satisfied in skipping the first occurrence, while the other will remain until another occurrence can be skipped.\par \par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.6g Some replacement effects say \ldblquote instead choose one \emdash .\rdblquote  Such effects are called }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 modal replacement effects.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  The mode is chosen as the replacement effect is applied. If a modal replacement effect would apply to multiple events, a different mode may be chosen for each event. A modal replacement effect doesn\rquote t invoke itself repeatedly, regardless of which mode was chosen. You may not choose modes that are impossible.\par \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.6h Some effects replace card draws. These effects are applied even if no cards could be drawn because there are no cards in the affected player\rquote s library. If an effect replaces a draw within a sequence of card draws, all actions required by the replacement are completed, if possible, before resuming the sequence. If an effect would have a player both draw a card and perform an additional action on that card, and the draw is replaced, the additional action is not performed on any cards that are drawn as a result of that replacement effect.\par \par 419.6i Some replacement effects modify how a permanent would be put into play. (See rules 419.1b\endash c.) Such effects check only the copiable values of the characteristics of that permanent as it would exist in play. Continuous effects that affected its characteristics in its previous zone or that will affect its characteristics once it\rquote s in play are not taken into account. Replacement effects that have already modified how it would be put into play are taken into account, however. (See rule 503.5.) }{\f0\cf1\insrsid3761202\charrsid11154 Some permanents have static abilities that modify how a general subset of permanents would be put into play; such an ability doesn\rquote t affect the permanent itself or any permanents coming into play at the same time as it.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Voice of All says \ldblquote As Voice of All comes into play, choose a color\rdblquote  and \ldblquote Voice of All has protection from the chosen color.\rdblquote  An effect creates a token that\rquote s a copy of Voice of All. As that token is put into play, its controller chooses a color for it.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example: }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Yixlid Jailer says \ldblquote Cards in graveyards have no abilities.\rdblquote  Scarwood Treefolk says \ldblquote Scarwood Treefolk is put into play tapped.\rdblquote  A Scarwood Treefolk that\rquote s put into play from a graveyard is put into play tapped.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Orb of Dreams is an artifact that says \ldblquote Permanents come into play tapped.\rdblquote  It will not affect itself, so Orb of Dreams is put into play untapped.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.7. Prevention Effects\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.7a Prevention effects usually apply to damage that would be dealt.\par \par 419.7b Some prevention effects generated by the resolution of a spell or ability refer to a specific amount of damage\emdash for example, \ldblquote Prevent the next 3 damage that would be dealt to target creature or player this turn.\rdblquote  These work like shields. Each 1 damage that would be dealt to the \ldblquote shielded\rdblquote  creature or player is prevented. Preventing 1 damage reduces the remaining shield by 1. If damage would be dealt to the shielded creature or player by two or more applicable sources at the same time, the player or the controller of the creature chooses which damage the shield prevents first. Once the shield has been reduced to 0, any remaining damage is dealt normally. Such effects count only the amount of damage; the number of events or sources dealing it doesn\rquote t matter.\par \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.7c Some prevention effects generated by static abilities refer to a specific amount of damage\emdash for example, \ldblquote If a source would deal damage to you, prevent 1 of that damage.\rdblquote  Such an effect prevents only the indicated amount of damage from any applicable source at any given time. It will apply separately to damage from other applicable sources, or to damage that would be dealt by the same source at a different time.\par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.7d Some prevention effects prevent the next N damage that would be dealt to each of a number of untargeted creatures. Such an effect creates a prevention shield for each applicable creature when the spell or ability that generates that effect resolves.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example: }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Wojek Apothecary has an ability that says \ldblquote \{T\}: Prevent the next 1 damage that would be dealt to target creature and each other creature that shares a color with it this turn.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \rdblquote  When the ability resolves, it gives the target creature and each other creature in play that shares a color with it at that time a shield preventing the next 1 damage that would be dealt to it. Changing creatures\rquote  colors after the ability resolves doesn\rquote t add or remove shields, and creatures that come into play later in the turn don\rquote t get the shield.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.8. Sources of Damage\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.8a Some effects apply to damage from a source\emdash for example, \ldblquote The next time a red source of your choice would deal damage to you this turn, prevent that damage.\rdblquote  If an effect requires a player to choose a source, he or she may choose a permanent; a spell on the stack (including an artifact, creature, enchantment, planeswalker spell); any card or permanent referred to by an object on the stack; or a creature that assigned combat damage on the stack, even if the creature is no longer in play or is no longer a creature. The source is chosen when the effect is created. If the player chooses a permanent, the prevention will apply to the next damage from that permanent, regardless of whether it\rquote s from one of that permanent\rquote s abilities or combat damage dealt by it. If the player chooses an artifact, creature, enchantment, planeswalker spell, the prevention will apply to any damage from that spell and from the permanent that it becomes when it resolves.\par \par 419.8b Some effects from spells and abilities prevent or replace damage from sources with certain properties, such as a creature or a source of a particular color. When the source would deal damage, the \ldblquote shield\rdblquote  rechecks the source\rquote s properties. If the properties no longer match, the damage isn\rquote t prevented or replaced. If for any reason the shield prevents no damage or replaces no damage, the shield isn\rquote t used up.\par \par 419.8c Some effects from static abilities prevent or replace damage from sources with certain properties. For these effects, the prevention or replacement applies to sources that are permanents with that property and to any sources that aren\rquote t in play that have that property.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.9. Interaction of Replacement or Prevention Effects\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 419.9a If two or more replacement or prevention effects are attempting to modify the way an event affects an object or player, the affected object\rquote s controller (or its owner if it has no controller) or the affected player chooses one to apply. Then the other effect applies if it is still appropriate. If one or more of the applicable replacement effects is a self-replacement effect (see rule 419.6d), that effect is applied before any other replacement effects. If two or more players have to make these choices at the same time, choices are made in APNAP order (see rule 103.4).\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Two permanents are in play. One is an enchantment that reads \ldblquote If a card would be put into a graveyard, instead remove it from the game,\rdblquote  and the other is a creature that reads \ldblquote If [this creature] would be put into a graveyard from play, instead shuffle it into its owner\rquote s library.\rdblquote  The controller of the creature that would be destroyed decides which replacement to apply first; the other does nothing.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 419.9b A replacement effect can become applicable to an event as the result of another replacement effect that modifies the event.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  One effect reads \ldblquote For each 1 life you would gain, instead draw a card,\rdblquote  and another reads \ldblquote If you would draw a card, return a card from your graveyard to your hand instead.\rdblquote  Both effects combine (regardless of the order they came into existence): Instead of gaining 1 life, the player puts a card from his or her graveyard into his or her hand.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 420. State-Based Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 420.1. State-based effects are a special category that apply only to those conditions listed below. Abilities that watch for a specified game state are triggered abilities, not state-based effects. (See rule 404, \ldblquote Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 420.2. State-based effects are always active and are not controlled by any player.\par \par 420.3. Whenever a player would get priority (see rule 408, \ldblquote Timing of Spells and Abilities\rdblquote ), the game checks for any of the listed conditions for state-based effects. All applicable effects resolve as a single event, then the check is repeated. Once no more state-based effects have been generated, triggered abilities go on the stack, and then the appropriate player gets priority. This check is also made during the cleanup step (see rule 314); if any of the listed conditions apply, the active player receives priority.\par \par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 420.4. Unlike triggered abilities, state-based effects pay no attention to what happens during the resolution of a spell or ability.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A player controls a creature with the ability \ldblquote This creature\rquote s power and toughness are each equal to the number of cards in your hand\rdblquote  and plays a spell whose effect is \ldblquote Discard your hand, then draw seven cards.\rdblquote  The creature will temporarily have toughness 0 in the middle of the spell\rquote s resolution but will be back up to toughness 7 when the spell finishes resolving. Thus the creature will survive when state-based effects are checked. In contrast, an ability that triggers when the player has no cards in hand goes on the stack after the spell resolves, because its trigger event happened during resolution.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 420.5. The state-based effects are as follows:\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 420.5a A player with 0 or less life loses the game.\par \par 420.5b A creature with toughness 0 or less is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. Regeneration can\rquote t replace this event.\par \par 420.5c A creature with lethal damage, but greater than 0 toughness, is destroyed. Lethal damage is an amount of damage greater than or equal to a creature\rquote s toughness. Regeneration can replace this event.\par \par 420.5d An Aura attached to an illegal object or player, or not attached to an object or player, is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard.\par \par 420.5e If two or more legendary permanents with the same name are in play, all are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. This is called the \ldblquote legend rule.\rdblquote  If only one of those permanents is legendary, this rule doesn\rquote t apply.\par \par 420.5f A token in a zone other than the in-play zone ceases to exist.\par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 420.5g A player who attempted to draw a card from an empty library since the last time state-based effects were checked loses the game.\par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 420.5h A player with ten or more poison counters loses the game.\par \par 420.5i If two or more permanents have the supertype world, all except the one that has been a permanent with the world supertype in play for the shortest amount of time are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. In the event of a tie for the shortest amount of time, all are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. This is called the \ldblquote world rule.\rdblquote \par \par 420.5j A copy of a spell in a zone other than the stack ceases to exist. {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK35}A copy of a card in any zone other than the stack or the in-play zone ceases to exist.{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK35}\par \par 420.5k An Equipment or Fortification attached to an illegal permanent becomes unattached from that permanent. It remains in play.\par \par 420.5m A permanent that\rquote s neither an Aura, an Equipment, nor a Fortification, but is attached to another permanent, becomes unattached from that permanent. It remains in play.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 420.5n If a permanent has both a +1/+1 counter and a -1/-1 counter on it, N +1/+1 and N -1/-1 counters are removed from it, where N is the smaller of the number of +1/+1 and -1/-1 counters on it.}{\f0\insrsid3761202 \par \par 420.5p A planeswalker with loyalty 0 is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard.\par \par 420.5q }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 If two or more }{\f0\insrsid3761202 planeswalkers}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  }{\f0\insrsid3761202 that share a planeswalker type}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  are in play, all are pu}{\f0\insrsid3761202 t into their owners\rquote  graveyards.}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 421. Handling \ldblquote Infinite\rdblquote  Loops\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 421.1. Occasionally the game can get into a state in which a set of actions could be repeated forever. These rules (sometimes called the \ldblquote infinity rules\rdblquote ) govern how to break such loops.\par \par 421.2. If the loop contains one or more optional actions and one player controls them all, that player chooses a number. The loop is treated as repeating that many times or until another player intervenes, whichever comes first.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK33}421.3. If a loop contains optional actions controlled by two players and actions by both of those players are required to continue the loop, the first player (or the first involved player after the active player in turn order) chooses a number. The other player then has two choices. He or she can choose a lower number, in which case the loop continues that number of times plus whatever fraction is necessary for the active player to \ldblquote have the last word.\rdblquote  Or he or she can agree to the number the first player chose, in which case the loop continues that number of times plus whatever fraction is necessary for the second player to \ldblquote have the last word.\rdblquote  (Note that either fraction may be zero.) This sequence of choices is extended to all applicable players if there are more than two players involved.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK33}Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  In a two-player game, one player controls a creature with the ability \ldblquote \{0\}: [This creature] gains flying,\rdblquote  and another player controls a permanent with the ability \ldblquote \{0\}: Target creature loses flying.\rdblquote  The \ldblquote infinity rule\rdblquote  ensures that regardless of which player initiated the gain/lose flying ability, the nonactive player will always have the final choice and therefore be able to determine whether the creature has flying. (Note that this assumes that the first player attempted to give the creature flying at least once.)\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 421.4. If the loop contains only mandatory actions, the game ends in a draw. (See rule 102.4b.)\par \par 421.5. If the loop contains optional actions controlled by different players and these actions don\rquote t depend on one another, the active player chooses a number. In APNAP order, the nonactive players can each either agree to that number or choose a higher number. Note that this rule applies even if the actions could exist in separate loops rather than in a single loop.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 422. Handling Illegal Actions\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 422.1. If a player realizes that he or she can\rquote t legally take an action after starting to do so, the entire action is reversed and any payments already made are canceled. No abilities trigger and no effects apply as a result of an undone action. If the action was playing a spell, the spell returns to the zone it came from. The player may also reverse any legal mana abilities played while making the illegal play, unless mana from them or from any triggered mana abilities they triggered was spent on another mana ability that wasn\rquote t reversed. Players may not reverse actions that moved cards to a library or from a library to any zone other than the stack.\par \par 422.2. When reversing illegal spells and abilities, the player who had priority retains it and may take another action or pass. The player may redo the reversed action in a legal way or take any other action allowed by the rules.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 423. Drawing a Card\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 423.1. A player draws a card by putting the top card of his or her library into his or her hand. This is done as a game action during each player\rquote s draw step. It may also be done as part of a cost or effect of a spell or ability.\par \par 423.2. Cards may only be drawn one at a time. If a player is instructed to draw multiple cards, that player performs that many individual card draws.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 423.2a If an effect instructs more than one player to draw cards, the active player performs all of his or her draws first, then each other player in turn order does the same.\par \par 4}{\f0\insrsid3761202 23}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 .2b If an effect instructs more than one player to draw cards in a Two-Headed Giant game, first the primary player (seated on the right) on the active team performs all of his or her draws, then the secondary player on that team performs all of his or her draws, then the nonactive team does the same.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 423.3. If there are no cards in a player\rquote s library and an effect offers that player the choice to draw a card, that player may choose to do so. See rule 413.2c.\par \par 423.4. A player who attempts to draw a card from an empty library loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5g.)\par \par 423.5. If an effect moves cards from a player\rquote s library to that player\rquote s hand without using the word \ldblquote draw,\rdblquote  the player has not drawn those cards. This makes a difference for abilities that trigger on drawing cards or that replace card draws, as well as if the player\rquote s library is empty.}{\f0\highlight7\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 423.6. Some effects replace card draws.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 423.6a An effect that replaces a card draw is applied even if no cards could be drawn because there are no cards in the affected player\rquote s library.\par \par 423.6b If an effect replaces a draw within a sequence of card draws, the replacement effect is completed before resuming the sequence.\par }{\f0\highlight4\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 423.6c Some effects perform additional actions on a card after it\rquote s drawn. If the draw is replaced, the additional action is not performed on any cards that are drawn as a result of that replacement effect or any subsequent replacement effects.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 424. Costs\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 424.1. A cost is an action or payment necessary to take another action.\par \par 424.2. A player can\rquote t pay a cost unless he or she has the necessary resources to pay it fully. For example, a player with only 1 life can\rquote t pay a cost of 2 life, and a permanent that\rquote s already tapped can\rquote t be tapped to pay a cost. See rule 203, \ldblquote Mana Cost and Color,\rdblquote  and rule 403, \ldblquote Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par 424.3. Unpayable costs can\rquote t be paid. (See rule 203.1b.)\par \par 424.4. What a player actually needs to do to pay a cost may be changed or reduced by effects. If the mana component of a cost is reduced to nothing by cost reduction effects, it is considered to