n\rquote t \ldblquote cancel\rdblquote  one another.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  If a player controls a snow Forest, that player can\rquote t block an attacking creature with snow forestwalk even if he or she also controls a creature with snow forestwalk.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.6e Multiple instances of the same }{\f0\insrsid3761202 kind}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  of landwalk or snow landwalk on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.7. Protection\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.7a Protection is a static ability, written \ldblquote Protection from [quality].\rdblquote  This quality is usually a color (as in \ldblquote protection from black\rdblquote ) but can be any characteristic value. If the quality is a }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type, subtype, or supertype, the protection applies to sources that are permanents with that }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type, subtype, or supertype and to any sources not in play that are of that }{\f0\insrsid3761202 card }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 type, subtype, or supertype. This is an exception to rule 200.9.\par \par 502.7b A permanent or player with protection can\rquote t be targeted by spells with the stated quality and can\rquote t be targeted by abilities from a source with the stated quality.\par \par 502.7c A permanent or player with protection can\rquote t be enchanted by Auras that have the stated quality. Such Auras attached to the permanent or player with protection will be put into their owners\rquote  graveyards as a state-based effect. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.7d A permanent with protection can\rquote t be equipped by Equipment that have the stated quality or fortified by Fortifications that have the stated quality. Such Equipment or Fortifications become unattached from that permanent, but remain in play. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.7e Any damage that would be dealt by sources that have the stated quality to a permanent or player that has protection is prevented.\par \par 502.7f }{\f0\insrsid3761202 Attacking }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 creature}{\f0\insrsid3761202 s}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  with protection can\rquote t be blocked by creatures that have the stated quality.\par \par 502.7g Multiple instances of protection from the same quality on the same permanent or player are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.8. Shadow\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.8a Shadow is an evasion ability.\par \par 502.8b A creature with shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures without shadow, and a creature without shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures with shadow. (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.8c Multiple instances of shadow on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.9. Trample\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.9a Trample is a static ability that modifies the rules for assigning an attacking creature\rquote s combat damage. A creature with trample has no special abilities when blocking or dealing noncombat damage. (See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.9b The controller of an attacking creature with trample first assigns damage to the creature(s) blocking it. If all those blocking creatures are assigned lethal damage, any remaining damage is assigned as its controller chooses among those blocking creatures and the player}{\f0\insrsid3761202  or planeswalker the creature is attacking}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 . When checking for assigned lethal damage, take into account damage already on the creature and damage from other creatures that will be assigned at the same time (see rule 502.9e). The controller need not assign lethal damage to all those blocking creatures but in that case can\rquote t assign any damage to the player}{\f0\insrsid3761202  or planeswalker it\rquote s attacking}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 .\par \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\insrsid3761202\charrsid3960444 502.9c If an attacking creature with trample is blocked, but there are no creatures blocking it when damage is assigned, all its damage is assigned to the player or planeswalker it\rquote s attacking.\par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.9d Assigning damage from a creature with trample considers only the actual toughness of a blocking creature, not any abilities or effects that might change the final amount of damage dealt.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A 6/6 green creature with trample is blocked by a 2/2 creature with protection from green. The attacking creature\rquote s controller must assign at least 2 damage to the blocker, even though that damage will be prevented by the blocker\rquote s protection ability. The attacking creature\rquote s controller can then choose to assign the rest of the damage to the defending player.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.9e When there are several attacking creatures, it\rquote s legal to assign damage from those without trample so as to maximize the damage of those with trample.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A 2/2 creature with an ability that enables it to block multiple attackers blocks two attackers: a 1/1 with no special abilities a 3/3 with trample. The attacking player could assign 1 damage from the first attacker and 1 damage from the second to the blocking creature, and 2 damage to the defending player from the creature with trample.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.9f Multiple instances of trample on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.10. Banding\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.10a Banding is a static ability that modifies the rules for declaring attackers and assigning combat damage.\par \par 502.10b As a player declares attackers, he or she may declare that any number of those creatures with banding, and up to one of those creatures without banding, are all in a \ldblquote band.\rdblquote  }{\f0\insrsid3761202 All of those creatures must attack the same player or planeswalker. }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 (Defending players can\rquote t declare bands but may use banding in a different way; see rule 502.10h.)\par \par 502.10c A player may declare as many attacking bands as he or she wants, but each creature may be a member of only one of them.\par \par 502.10d Once an attacking band has been announced, it lasts for the rest of combat, even if something later removes the banding ability from one or more creatures. However, creatures in a band that are removed from combat are also removed from the band.\par \par 502.10e If an attacking creature becomes blocked by a creature, each other creature in the same band as the attacking creature becomes blocked by that same blocking creature.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A player attacks with a band consisting of a creature with flying and a creature with swampwalk. The defending player, who controls a Swamp, can block the flying creature if able. If he or she does, then the creature with swampwalk will also become blocked by the blocking creature(s).\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.10f Banding doesn\rquote t cause attacking creatures to share abilities, nor does it remove any abilities. The attacking creatures in a band are separate permanents.\par \par 502.10g If one member of a band would become blocked due to an effect, the entire band becomes blocked.\par \par 502.10h A player who controls an attacking creature with banding chooses how combat damage is assigned by creatures blocking that creature. A player who controls a blocking creature with banding chooses how combat damage is assigned by creatures it blocks. If the creature had banding when it attacked or blocked but the ability was removed before the combat damage step, damage is assigned normally.\par \par 502.10i Multiple instances of banding on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.11. Bands with Other\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.11a Bands with other is a special form of banding. If an effect causes a permanent to lose banding, the permanent loses all bands with other abilities as well.\par \par 502.11b An attacking creature with \ldblquote bands with other [}{\f0\insrsid3761202 quality}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 ]\rdblquote  can form an attacking band with other creatures that have the same \ldblquote bands with other [}{\f0\insrsid3761202 quality}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 ]\rdblquote  ability. Creatures with banding can also join this band, but creatures without banding can\rquote t. The creatures in this band don\rquote t have to have the creature type specified in the \ldblquote bands with other [}{\f0\insrsid3761202 quality}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 ]\rdblquote  ability. Blocking this band follows the same general rules as for banding.\par \par 502.11c If an attacking creature is blocked by at least two creatures with the same \ldblquote bands with other [}{\f0\insrsid3761202 quality}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 ]\rdblquote  ability, the defending player chooses how the attacking creature\rquote s damage is assigned. Similarly, if a blocking creature blocks at least two attacking creatures with the same \ldblquote bands with other [}{\f0\insrsid3761202 quality}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 ]\rdblquote  ability, the attacking player chooses how the blocking creature\rquote s damage is assigned.\par \par 502.11d Multiple instances of bands with other of the same }{\f0\insrsid3761202 kind}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.12. Rampage\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.12a Rampage is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Rampage N\rdblquote  means \ldblquote Whenever this creature becomes blocked, it gets +N/+N until end of turn for each creature blocking it beyond the first.\rdblquote  (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.12b The rampage bonus is calculated only once per combat, when the triggered ability resolves. Adding or removing blockers later in combat won\rquote t change the bonus.\par \par 502.12c If a creature has multiple instances of rampage, each triggers separately.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.13. Cumulative Upkeep\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid3761202 502.13a Cumulative upkeep is a triggered ability that imposes an increasing cost on a permanent. \ldblquote Cumulative upkeep [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, put an age counter on this permanent. Then you may pay [cost] for each age counter on it. If you don\rquote t, sacrifice it.\rdblquote  If [cost] has choices associated with it, each choice is made separately for each age counter, then either the entire set of costs is paid, or none of them is paid. Partial payments aren\rquote t allowed.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid3761202 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A creature has \ldblquote Cumulative upkeep \{W\} or \{U\}\rdblquote  and two age counters on it. When its ability next triggers and resolves, the creature\rquote s controller puts an age counter on it and then may pay \{W\}\{W\}\{W\}, \{W\}\{W\}\{U\}, \{W\}\{U\}\{U\}, or \{U\}\{U\}\{U\} to keep the creature in play.\par }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A creature has \ldblquote Cumulative upkeep\emdash Sacrifice a creature\rdblquote  and one age counter on it. When its ability next triggers and resolves, its controller can\rquote t choose the same creature to sacrifice twice. Either two different creatures must be sacrificed, or the creature with cumulative upkeep must be sacrificed.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.13b If a permanent has multiple instances of cumulative upkeep, each triggers separately. However, the age counters are not linked to any particular ability; each cumulative upkeep ability will count the total number of age counters on the permanent at the time that ability resolves.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A creature has two instances of \ldblquote Cumulative upkeep\emdash Pay 1 life.\rdblquote  The creature currently has no counters but both cumulative upkeep abilities trigger. When the first ability resolves, the controller adds a counter and then chooses to pay 1 life. When the second ability resolves, the controller adds another counter and then chooses to pay an additional 2 life.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.14. Vigilance\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.14a Vigilance is a static ability that modifies the rules for the declare attackers step.\par \par 502.14b Attacking doesn\rquote t cause creatures with vigilance to tap. (See rule 308, \ldblquote Declare Attackers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.14c Multiple instances of vigilance on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.15. Phasing\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.15a Phasing is a static ability that modifies the rules of the untap step.\par \par 502.15b During each player\rquote s untap step, before the active player untaps his or her permanents, all permanents with phasing the player controls phase out. Simultaneously, all objects that had phased out under that player\rquote s control phase in. (See rule 217.8, \ldblquote Phased Out,\rdblquote  and rule 302.1.)\par \par 502.15c If an effect causes a player to skip his or her untap step, the phasing event simply doesn\rquote t occur that turn.\par \par 502.15d Permanents phasing in or out don\rquote t trigger any comes-into-play or leaves-play abilities, and effects that modify how a permanent comes into play are ignored. Abilities and effects that specifically mention phasing can modify or trigger on these events, however. (Because no player receives priority during the untap step, any abilities triggering off of the phasing event won\rquote t go onto the stack until the upkeep step begins.)\par \par 502.15e When a permanent phases out, all damage dealt to it is removed.\par \par 502.15f A card that returns to play from the phased-out zone is considered the same permanent it was when it left. This is an exception to rule 217.1c, which stipulates that a permanent \ldblquote forgets\rdblquote  its previous existence when it changes zones.\par \par 502.15g Effects with limited duration and delayed triggered abilities that specifically reference a permanent will be unable to further affect that permanent if it phases out. However, other effects that reference the permanent (including effects with unlimited duration) can affect the permanent when it returns to play.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  A creature is affected by Giant Growth and then phases out during the same turn. If the creature phases back in somehow before the turn is over, it won\rquote t get the +3/+3 bonus from the Giant Growth because its effect has a limited duration.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.15h Phased-out cards \ldblquote remember\rdblquote  their past histories and will return to play in the same state. They \ldblquote remember\rdblquote  any counters they had on them, any choices made when they first came into play, whether they were flipped when they left play, and whether they were tapped or untapped when they left play. They also \ldblquote remember\rdblquote  who controlled them when they phased out, although they may phase in under the control of a different player if a control effect with limited duration has expired.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Example:}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  Diseased Vermin reads, in part, \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, Diseased Vermin deals X damage to target opponent previously dealt damage by it, where X is the number of infection counters on it.\rdblquote  If Diseased Vermin phases out, it \ldblquote remembers\rdblquote  how many counters it has and also which opponents it has previously damaged. When it phases back in, it will still be able to target those opponents with its upkeep-triggered ability.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.15i When a permanent phases out, any Auras, Equipment, or Fortifications attached to that permanent phase out at the same time. This alternate way of phasing out is known as phasing out \ldblquote indirectly.\rdblquote  An Aura, Equipment, or Fortification that phased out indirectly won\rquote t phase in by itself, but instead phases in along with the card it\rquote s attached to.\par \par 502.15j If an Aura, Equipment, or Fortification phased out directly (rather than phasing out along with the permanent it\rquote s attached to), then it \ldblquote remembers\rdblquote  the permanent it was attached to and returns to play attached to that permanent. If an Aura phases in but it\rquote s no longer legal for it to be attached to the object or player it was attached to, the Aura returns to play and then is placed in its owner\rquote s graveyard. This is a state-based effect; see rule 420. If an Equipment or Fortification phases in but it\rquote s no longer legal for it to be attached to the permanent it was attached to, the Equipment or Fortification returns to play and then stays in play, not attached to anything. This is a state-based effect; see rule 420.\par \par 502.15k Permanents that phase in keep the same timestamps (see rules 418.5d and 418.5e) they had when they phased out. This doesn\rquote t change the fact that the permanents phase in simultaneously, however.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK52}502.15m A permanent that phases in can attack and tap to play abilities as though it had haste. This applies even if that permanent phased out and phased back in the turn it came into play. The permanent remains able to attack and tap to play abilities until it changes controllers or leaves play.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK52}\par 502.15n A spell or ability that targets a permanent will resolve normally with respect to that permanent if the permanent phases out and back in before the spell or ability resolves.\par \par 502.15p Multiple instances of phasing on the same permanent are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK38}502.16. Buyback\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.16a Buyback appears on some instants and sorceries. It represents two static abilities that function while the spell is on the stack. \ldblquote Buyback [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may pay an additional [cost] as you play this spell\rdblquote  and \ldblquote If the buyback cost was paid, put this spell into its owner\rquote s hand instead of into that player\rquote s graveyard as it resolves.\rdblquote  Paying a spell\rquote s buyback cost follows the rules for paying additional costs in rules 409.1b and 409.1f-h.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK38}\par 502.17. Horsemanship\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.17a Horsemanship is an evasion ability that appeared in the }{\i\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Portal Three Kingdoms\u8482\'aa}{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525  set.\par \par 502.17b A creature with horsemanship can\rquote t be blocked by creatures without horsemanship. A creature with horsemanship can block a creature with or without horsemanship. (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.17c Multiple instances of horsemanship on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.18. Cycling\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 502.18a Cycling is an activated ability that functions only while the card with cycling is in a player\rquote s hand. \ldblquote Cycling [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote [Cost], Discard this card: Draw a card.\rdblquote \par \par 502.18b Although the cycling ability is playable only if the card is in a player\rquote s hand, it continues to exist while the object is in play and in all other zones. Therefore objects with cycling will be affected by effects that depend on objects having one or more activated abilities.\par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 502.18c Some cards with cycling have abilities that trigger when they\rquote re cycled. \ldblquote When you cycle [this card]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote When you discard [this card] to pay a cycling cost.\rdblquote  These abilities trigger from the graveyard.