ered.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 504. Face-Down Spells and Permanents\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 504.1. Two cards (Illusionary Mask and Ixidron) and the morph ability (see rule 502.26) allow spells and permanents to be face down.\par \par 504.2. Face-down spells on the stack, face-down permanents in play, and face-down cards in the phased-out zone have no characteristics other than those listed by the ability or rules that allowed the card, spell, or permanent to be turned face down. Any listed characteristics are the copiable values of that object\rquote s characteristics. (See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects,\rdblquote  and rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects.\rdblquote ) Objects that are put into play face down are turned face down before they come into play, so the permanent\rquote s comes-into-play abilities won\rquote t trigger (if triggered) or have any effect (if static). Objects that are played face down are turned face down before they are put onto the stack, so effects that care about the characteristics of a spell will see only the face-down spell\rquote s characteristics. Any effects or prohibitions that would apply to playing an object with these characteristics (and not the face-up object\rquote s characteristics) are applied to playing this object.\par \par 504.3. {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK15}{\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK40}At any time, you may look at a face-down spell you control on the stack, a face-down permanent you control, or a face-down card in the phased-out zone you controlled when it phased out. {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK15}You can\rquote t look at face-down cards in any other zone, face-down spells or permanents controlled by another player, or face-down cards in the phased-out zone last controlled by another player.{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK40} The ability or rules that allow a permanent to be face down may also allow the permanent\rquote s controller to turn it face up. Spells normally can\rquote t be turned face up.\par \par 504.4. If you control multiple face-down spells on the stack or face-down permanents in play, you must ensure at all times that your face-down spells and permanents can be easily differentiated from each other. This includes, but is not limited to, knowing the order spells were played, the order that face-down permanents came into play, which creature attacked last turn, and any other differences between face-down spells or permanents. Common methods for distinguishing between face-down objects include using counters or dice to mark the different objects, or clearly placing those objects in order on the table.\par \par 504.5. As a face-down permanent is turned face up, its copiable values revert to its normal copiable values. Any effects that have been applied to the face-down permanent still apply to the face-up permanent. Any abilities relating to the permanent coming into play don\rquote t trigger and don\rquote t have any effect, because the permanent has already come into play.\par \par 504.6. If a face-down permanent moves from the in-play zone to any zone other than the phased-out zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. If a phased-out face-down object moves to any zone other than the in-play zone, its owner must reveal it as he or she moves it. If a face-down spell moves from the stack to any zone other than the in-play zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. At the end of each game, all face-down objects in play, in the phased-out zone, or on the stack must be revealed to all players.\par \par 504.7. If a face-down permanent becomes a copy of another permanent, its copiable values become the copiable values of that permanent, as modified by its face-down status. Its characteristics therefore remain the same: the characteristics listed by the ability or rules that allowed it to be turned face down. However, if it is turned face up, its copiable values become the values it copied from the other permanent.\par \par 504.8. If a face-down permanent would have an \ldblquote As [this permanent] is turned face up . . .\rdblquote  ability after it\rquote s turned face up, that ability is applied while that permanent is being turned face up, not afterward.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK11}505. Split Cards\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 \par 505.1. Split cards have two card faces on a single card. The back of a split card is the normal }{\b\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 Magic: The Gathering }{\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 card back.\par \par 505.2. In every zone except the stack, split cards have two sets of characteristics and two converted mana costs. As long as a split card is a spell on the stack, only the characteristics of the half being played exist. The other half\rquote s characteristics are treated as though they didn\rquote t exist.\par \par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid3761202 {\f0\insrsid3761202\charrsid10638525 505.3. Each split card that consists of two halves with different colored mana symbols in their mana costs is a multicolored card while it\rquote s not a spell on the stack. While it\rquote s a spell on the sta